consent:
UC Davis and UC Davis Health

Consent to Participate in Research



Title of study:  Personalizing Personality

Investigator: Dr. Emorie D. Beck, PhD, Assistant Professor, Department of Psychology, UC Davis



Introduction and Purpose 

You are being invited to join a research study.  



The purpose of this study is to see if allowing individuals to tell us which questions we should ask them provide better summaries of their personalities and their daily lives than standard batteries of personality and daily life. 



If you agree to be in this research, you will be asked to complete one baseline survey and 105 experience sampling surveys. In this baseline survey, you will complete a variety of measures about your personality, your emotions, and your daily life.   It will take about 45 minutes to complete the survey. In the experience sampling portion, you will complete up to 5, 2 minute surveys per day for up to 3 weeks. Each of these will take about 2-3 minutes to complete. At the end of the three weeks, you will receive a personalized report summarizing your experience sampling responses.



There is no direct benefit to you from taking part in this study. We hope that the research will help you to understand your daily thoughts, feelings, behaviors, and experiences.



The risks of this research are minimal. Some of the questions might make you feel uncomfortable or upset.  You do not have to answer any of the questions you do not want to answer.  



Confidentiality

As with all research, there is a chance that confidentiality could be compromised; however, we are taking precautions to minimize this risk. Your responses to the survey will not include information that identifies you. This identifiable information will be handled as confidentially as possible. However, individuals from UC Davis who oversee research may access your data during audits or other monitoring activities. 



To minimize the risks of breach of confidentiality, we will store all identifiable information (name, phone number for text messages) separately from all survey responses in a password protected, encrypted file. Your survey results will only be linked to you via a participant ID. Only you and the PI (Dr. Beck) will have access to this ID and to identifiable information.



The data we collect with your identifiable information (e.g., your name, medical record number, or date of birth) as a part of this study may be used to answer other research questions or may be shared with other investigators for other research. If we do so, we will remove all identifiable information before use or sharing. Once identifiers have been removed, we will not ask your consent for the use or sharing of your data in other research. In addition, data that have been de-identified will be uploaded to the Open Science Framework for other researchers to access and use.



Compensation

To thank you for participating in this research study, you will two forms of compensation, First, for the baseline survey, you will receive a $10 Amazon gift card emailed to you within 2 weeks after you complete it. Second, for every experience sampling survey you complete, you will receive $0.50 (maximum $63 for perfect completion rate) as an Amazon gift card emailed to you within 2 weeks of the end of the experience sampling portion of the study. If your completion rate is at 90% (94 surveys), you will receive a bonus of $10 applied to your experience sampling Amazon gift card. 



Rights

Taking part in research is completely voluntary.  You are free to decline to take part in the project.  You can decline to answer any questions and you can stop taking part in the project at any time.  Whether or not you choose to take part, or answer any question, or stop taking part in the project, there will be no penalty to you or loss of benefits to which you are otherwise entitled.



Questions

If you have any questions about this research, please feel free to contact the investigator at 573-690-0133 or edbeck@ucdavis.edu.



If you have any questions about your rights or treatment as a research participant in this study, please contact the UC Davis, Institutional Review Board by phone: 916 703 9158 or by email: HS-IRBEducation@ucdavis.edu.



If you agree to take part in the research, please print a copy of this page to keep for future reference, then click on the “Accept” button below.”

GenItems_narr:
Tell us about you and your life:

 

We want to understand your daily psychological, social, and emotional experiences; your behaviors; the contexts you inhabit; and your daily life overall. To do so, we want to give you the opportunity to tell us what questions we should ask you related to your emotions, thoughts, behaviors, contexts, goals, identities, challenges, and more in everyday life. 



Please describe your typical daily thoughts, experiences, behaviors, contexts, beliefs, desires, and/or anything else you think is important below. You may say, for example, that “I’m usually very energetic, but I get tired after lunch;” “Most days, I feel excited about what I need to do, but on Wednesdays I have a lab course that ruins my mood;” or "When I'm around peers, I often feel out of place because I am a first gen student." Also think about your reasons for experiences/behaviors/etc. Is there another reason you get tired after lunch other than the time of day? What about that lab course ruins your mood? Do specific peers trigger your first gen identity more than others? There are no right or wrong answers. The goal is simply to help you think about yourself and everyday experiences as well as what you think drives those. 



Write as much as you think is necessary to understand your daily life. There are no length limits, but please write at least two paragraphs. Richer descriptions will provide us more information to help you understand whether your perception of your daily life mirrors your actual experiences, while less rich descriptions may limit our ability to answer these questions. It might be helpful to think about the people you might be with, the places you might go, and the things you might do in the next few weeks.

 

(The submit button will appear after five minutes.)

Next, we’d like you to take this text and try to extract words or phrases that we’ll have you rate in your daily life. For example, the phrase “I’m usually very energetic, but I get tired after lunch” could be broken into 2 (“energetic” and “tired after lunch”) or 3 (“energetic,” “tired,” and “lunch”) items.



There’s no right or wrong way to break these up. Rather, we want to break these up as they are meaningful for you. If, for example, lunch doesn’t matter much outside this context, then we may not need to measure it separately from tired. But, if you think your tiredness is driven by other factors than proximity to lunch, then you would want to split it up. We will be asking you to rate how true each of the words or phrases you provide are in the moment in the next phase of the study, so also think about how to phrase them to make answering that prompt on a response scale from 1 "Strongly Disagree" to 5 "Strongly Agree."

name: Catherine Pabalan
GenItems_narr:
I always wake up really tired. I have to be on my phone for a while playing games to get up. I work night shift 7 days on and then 7 days off so my sleeping schedule changes depending on the week. I always wake up really hungry too because me and my boyfriend eat dinner at 5pm and then I don't end up eating until 10 or 11am the next day.

I spend most of my time with my boyfriend and some time with my family on weeks where I don't have work. I watch a lot of TV and tiktok and I feel at most peace when I crochet. I feel more energetic when I work out but that's only 3 times a week. I feel indifferent when at work. It's good work at a hospital so I feel satisfied that I'm helping people, but it's really monotonous work in a lab. I end up reading fanfiction for most of my hours at work and those are the best days.

My goal in life is to make enough money to travel and basically not have to worry about money. A job is just a job to me, not something that I want to strive higher in.

name: Destiny Jauregui
GenItems_narr: Usually on Sunday-Wednesday I feel like I have a lot of energy to get through the day and get things done, such as homework, attending lectures, grocery shopping and so on. I feel happy because I’m learning and retaining new interesting information but I also feel stressed on occasion because of the in-depth readings I’m required to read. But for the most part, on these days, I feel good and optimistic about where my life is going. However, Thursday-Saturday I feel a huge difference between what I’m like versus the previous days. I have a job I’ve been working at for 4 years and while I’m thankful to have a job, this job wears me out. I work 10 hours Thursday-Saturday and it’s very physically demanding. I come home feeling burnt out and frustrated that I’m even still at this job. I have nothing in common with my co-workers besides having the same job. Most of the people I work with are incompetent and unbearable to be around, really. Lol If I can leave early from work, I usually do. I know I won’t be at this job forever, but it does suck meanwhile; I just try to go through the motions without letting the externals get to me even more than they already have. I think I feel this way about this job mostly because I literally cannot relate to any of the individuals I work with and because, I mean, moving around for 10 hours a day with short breaks and lunches is exhausting in itself.
GenItems_Unique_item_11: Frustrated that I’m even still at this job

name: Qianshu Chen
GenItems_narr:
When I'm with people or friends, I tend to feel more fulfilled, even though I understand I could have meaningful alone time, I tend to get over-anxious. I like improving myself since I'm not a native speaker of English, so spending time with native English speakers makes me feel I'm always learning things. 
I enjoy the time working on campus because most of my coworkers are schoolmates and friends, It makes working way more relaxing and interesting. 
I don't like going to history class, especially the discussion section, I get so scared and anxious about what they expect me to do because I'm not good at history and kinda have no interest in it too.
I love spending time with my cat, his name is meatball.
GenItems_Unique_item_9: enjoy the time working on campus

name: Linda Ren
GenItems_narr:
I'm usually very busy every day. I have 3-4 lectures in the morning back to back, then attend a lunch talk (which offers free food so that's the highlight of my day), and have labs or more lectures in the afternoon. If I have more lectures right after the lunch talk, I most likely will fall asleep - perhaps from food coma or maybe because I get tired. I'm surrounded by a cohort of the smartest people I've ever worked with. I have always been the top student in my prior education experience, but here in vet school, everyone was a top student. I get stressed when my peers seem to know a lot more than I do or have mastered the lecture materials a lot better. 

However, I'm involved in a lot of extracurricular activities and I'm proud for what I do. Although they take away my study time, I enjoy organizing wet labs, provide free care for pets, and more. 

I am very fortunate to find a group of friends here, who I can hang out with and trust. 

I keep telling myself everyday that I need to study when I get home at night, but almost always fall asleep in my chair after the long day.

name: Sicily Brancatelli
GenItems_narr:
I believe that I have developed an inferiority complex. Recently, one of my suite-mates asked me to buy his friend a cake and didn’t offer to pay for it. Normally, if it were another mate, I wouldn’t have had an issue with this. I would say this interaction had upset me because of the individual who asked. For some context, I’m a first-gen hispanic woman and he is a white middle-class male. I understand how bad this must sound, but when he asked me that question I got upset. 
     Being white isn’t bad, but self-awareness of one’s privilege is always important. In the moment, I felt that he was entitled. I come from a low income family and attend UC Davis as a first-gen student. Despite my background, I always contribute to the dorm to the best of my abilities. My roommate and I constantly buy the cleaning supplies and accessories for the suite and we never even received a “thank you”. 
      I couldn’t wrap my head around why he would ask ME to buy HIS friend a cake - it made me all the more upset when I remembered he had more money than me. I would assume my pent-up frustration gradually built up and burst with that simple question. Of course, I didn’t lash out at him. I simply smiled. Ever since that encounter, I’ve been second guessing my character and I question whether or not I am drowning in my own self pity.

name: Allison Davis
GenItems_narr:
I spend most of my days with a very distinct split between me being traditionally productive, and me being traditionally unproductive. I say "traditionally" because now I'm aware that taking a breather for mental health is a form of being productive, but I digress. I'm either spending hours in class writing notes, studying, obsession over housing for next year, and signing up for SONA paid research participation, or getting completely absorbed in some sort of media and then spending hours trying to consume as much content from it as possible.

It's been pretty hard, I tested positive for Covid the day I was supposed to return and only came back yesterday, so I've missed the first 2-3 days of all of my classes. Luckily though I have a 4 day weekend, Friday-Monday off every week. All my classes this quarter are GE's that I could easily earn credit for at a CC if I fail, but nevertheless I've been raised with the mentality of anything lower than a B+ is failing so it stresses me out. 

I'm usually pretty anxious in the mornings-afternoons, and then very late at night. Usually it's because I'm overwhelmed and overthinking about all the things I have to do that day (mornings-afternoons) and then doing the same for the day to come (very late at night, like 12-2am). It probably doesn't help that I don't eat that much while I'm at college, usually just one meal a day and then a snack or two. In the later afternoon and for most of the night I try to completely relax and pick up wherever I left off last time in my media consumption. 

I would hang out with friends, but so far college has been a constant overstimulation for me. I'm used to having 1-2 close friends, then a lot of casual friends I see every so often, but now I have three roommates that are loud and are from a completely different crowd than I'm from. And with the looming uncomfortableness around the fact that my roommate threatened to kill herself last quarter (resulting in me having to call 911, which she then found out and got angry at me for), any form of social interaction with them is even more draining than talking to people usually are. I have one on campus friend (which I'm grateful for, if I had any more I would be socially drained 24/7) who is my current future roommate for next year, and although he's really nice and I'm happy we're friends, he's a very social guy and wants to hang out extremely often. I don't usually mind because when I'm with him, just like my other two good friends who are at different colleges, I get really energized talking with him, but afterwards I can't do anything but stare at a screen or nap for a few hours.

Besides going to classes Tuesday-Thursday, doing the occasional SONA study, and playing D&D with a group of more casual friends every Friday (with the one really good friend I mentioned earlier DMing), I spend the rest of my time on my computer or phone, usually my computer. I mainly play video games or watch TV shows/movies, but another large chunk I spend writing goofy things on Google Docs with a childhood friend of mine. I also spend a lot of time categorizing and keeping track of the things I play/watch, I have a multitude of lists and Google Sheets tracking my progress and opinions on almost all the media I consume.
GenItems_Unique_item_1: anxious in the mornings and afternoons
GenItems_Unique_item_2: absorbed in some sort of media
GenItems_Unique_item_9: spent a lot of time categorizing

name: Katelynn Phy
GenItems_narr:
There’s always something going on in my daily life. I tend to keep myself busy or do something throughout my day. It can be said that i do overwhelm myself, however that’s what allows me to be content. During the day, my ideal plans are to mostly get everything off my list done. Although sometimes that can be hard because I can find myself scrolling through social media mindlessly. This caused me to finish my work later than i wished, however at the start of this quarter, i’ve been doing better about limiting my social media use and prioritizing my work. However once it comes to night, it allows me to realize why i always keep myself busy or at least play some music. 
   I’m the type of person who does like being alone however not with my thoughts. Usually I’m seen wearing my headphones because it puts me into a better mood than when my mind is constantly running around, although there are times when that still happens. Throughout the day, I also tend to be a maladaptive daydreamer, which can unfortunately go for a long time. But overall, i’m really determined to create better habits for myself to become a more healthy happy person.

name: Allison york
GenItems_narr:
During the week I'm mostly with my 2 and 5 year old. Take and pick the 5 year old from school. Have two big dogs at home that somethings make it feel like ground hogs day. Between them and a 2 year old I feel there is constant cleaning that needs to be done. When I'm on top of the cleaning it's easy. However when the house gets to a point it gets overwhelming and exhausting. I'll feel like I'm just doing the dishes over and over and not making progress. 
My day feels the best when I get to go outside or be active by just going for a walk. Visiting with out of town family lifts my mood.
I love going to lake Tahoe and can be content just looking at the water or a walk in the forest. I could feel sick but if am in nature feel better and have energy

name: Amreen Kaur
GenItems_narr:
I’ve had an irregular sleeping schedule since middle school. I would stay up watching shows until the morning and that habit of sleeping late has continued until now. I get tired easily due to being depressed, lack of vitamin D maybe. I have trouble getting up in the morning and getting ready. I’m always in a hurry to get to places such as classes, actives, parties, events, work. I function better in high stress situations because I am forced to act. I enjoy talking to my best friends for hours and keeping up with my favorite music group and biggest interest: BTS. They make me very happy and give me energy. 

I have trouble eating healthy meals because I am always in a rush and rarely feel motivated to cook. I struggle understanding whether my procrastination/inaction on things such as homework, taking up opportunities, taking care of myself is due to laziness or depression. Being a good person and holding myself to a high moral standard is important but it often turns out to be more people pleasing. That prevents me from making the choices I really want because I am more concerned with being accepted by others. This comes from wanting to see my family happy when I was younger. I feel like i have to put others before myself to truly be happy because I hate confrontation and want good relationships with others. 

My main conflict in life is with healing myself from childhood issues. Despite moving away, i feel that my upbringing still has a great effect on me. While I wish I could change the past and have more emotional support and understanding from my parents I have to accept that isn’t possible and I have to improve myself where I am right now. 

I feel like im always in a constant cycle of ups and downs and I am not in control of my life. So I enjoy it a lot when I have the motivation too. I am very outgoing with my friends, but quiet and awkward in new settings and in big groups. I overthink a lot, again, because I want to make the right decisions. People’s approval is important to me. I love singing and listening to music. I like making my loved ones happy. I feel often that my happiness depends on others rather than myself. I feel too dependent on my parents and want to change that but it’s hard with how high tuition and rent is. Also, because finding the motivation to do anything is difficult for me.

name: Colin Test
GenItems_narr:
I am typically most energized and concentrated from when I wake up (~7:30am) to early afternoon (~2pm). This is when I typically do my “whiteboard tasks.” I have my goals for the day written on a white board, and they consist of reading specific papers, writing drafts and emails, watching lectures on stats and coding, going through tutorials or doing lab tasks (e.g., converting physio output into an analyzable format) in R, and recently, applying to jobs. There is no strict ordering to these tasks, but I usually do some combination of them on days I don’t go into lab for lab meetings (tuesdays 2:30-3:30pm) or one on one meetings (variable). These tasks are what I spend the bulk of my weekdays doing, and I feel most accomplished and “right with myself” if I have a productive days engaging in a combinations of these tasks. A productive day is usually interpreted as finishing 80-90% of the whiteboard tasks. My partner comes homes around 3:30pm and we usually talk about our days and plan on taking our dog on a walk. I very much value my partners arrival and our conversation, and if it doesn’t happen because either of us is busy, I am usually disappointed or annoyed. 

I am typically at a neutral affective level throughout that time (waking up to 3pm), unless I procrastinate. If I procrastinate I typically feel self critical and a little guilty. My time sitting at the computer is usually broken up by taking my dog out on a walk, cleaning the apartment, and eating lunch. I have a burst of energy and positive affect when I go outside with my dog at 12pm and when I go out around 4:30pm with my partner and my dog. If I do not go out with my partner around 4:30pm it almost always because I am skating with friends. Of course, this activity has a strong effect on my positive mood, feelings of affiliation, and sometimes, accomplishment. I eat dinner around 6, and that process (including cooking) is almost always an enjoyable one. After dinner I typically read a little next to my partner or we watch a tv show/movie. Some nights I play online games with friends from college and high school. 


My locations are usually constrained to:
My apartment
Research lab
Campus (walking dog)
Skate spot (skatepark, campus, BART station)
Friends house 

On weekends I try to get work (same as above) done in the morning but usually by noon we have plans to either go to parks, friends homes (local or out of town), play tennis/pickle ball, skate, or go on a hike. All of these activities almost always include friends and I feel very close and comfortable with them. No feelings of discomfort, and socializing gives me a boost in energy, talkativeness, and mental engagement (thinking of ideas, stories, jokes).

name: August Larson
GenItems_narr:
I wake up around 8 am on weekdays to get breakfast with my friends. It's a bit of a struggle to get up despite my alarm going off at 7:30 because I usually don't fall asleep until 1 am or later-- whether that be because we were hanging out for too late, or I was just on my phone for too long. Afterwards, I go back to my dorm and work on classwork until my classes begin at noon. The exception to this rule is on Fridays, in which we get breakfast at 9 and my classes start at 10. I dislike this, not just because of the change from my routine, but also because I have to go to two discussions on Fridays that force me to interact outside of my friend group. I'd say that I have a fair amount of friends, with our total group adding to around 10 people, and I get along with them much more than I ever did with my friends in high school. We all live on the same floor and mesh well. However, I have yet to make any friends in my major or in classes. In lectures I keep to myself and in discussions I only talk about what is relevant to the assignment at hand. I don't see the point in trying to interact further when I know it'll be too difficult to pass as anything other than visibly queer and neurodivergent.
After classes, I head back in the afternoon and either return to working on schoolwork or have some time to relax. I play multiple games on a daily basis-- one rhythm game, and one action-adventure, both "gacha" style mobile games. At 6:30 we have dinner(the most restrictive timing of all my daily activities, so much so that the meal is referred to as "Dinner At 6:30") and then hang out in my room until 9:30, where we listen to one of my friends read a book. Once reading is finished, I stay for another hour before returning to my room and getting ready for bed.

name: Aurolei Braroo
GenItems_narr: I am normally a very happy bubbly fun person but I have a lot going on underneath. Mental health recently has been difficult for me but luckily i have an incredible support system by way of my boyfriend and his family. Him and I have been together for over 4 years and his family is my family. Also I have a few friends how are my everything! Such incredible people! When I'm around peers, I often feel like I am part of something amazing because I tend to get along with others nicely. I hope to become a pediatrician one day as I love working with children and I also love medicine!

name: Max Kelly
GenItems_narr:
Hi, I'm Max!

As a brief introduction, I am a first year biological sciences major, with an interest in physiology and cellular biology. I use they/them pronouns. I have an interest in the arts as well, specifically pottery, sculpture, and glassblowing. I am Chinese American, and my Chinese roots do influence my daily life, mainly through the types of foods and activities I pursue on a daily basis. In the near future, I am looking forward to Lunar New Year and all the festivities that are going to ensue. 

In terms of my daily/weekly routines, I typically get up pretty early and after about thirty minutes have a decent amount of energy which I usually maintain until about three or so at which point I lose energy till about 6:30 when I have dinner, after which I usually have a fair amount of energy again until 12:00-1:00 am. My chemistry lab is a drag on my daily life, (Tuesday 4:00-7:00 pm) and it is a weekly source of dread but other than that none of my courses are particularly bothersome. I like to spend my time in the ceramics studio at the craft center after my courses are finished when time permits as I feel as though giving myself the opportunity to be creative after learning content through lectures for several hours straight is good for my mental health, it helps me decompress a little bit. I have no courses on Thursday and I look forward to having a day to play catch up a little bit and relax.

name: Brandon Greenleaf
GenItems_narr:
When I first wake up, I tend to feel excited about the day. I feel less excited on Tuesday and Thursday, just because the classes aren't as exciting. I also have a very late lab on Thursday which is sometimes stressful. I really enjoy chemistry, and look forward to every lecture (M,W,R). I usually enjoy lab, but I can get stressed out about having to work with my partner and finishing on time. School doesn't really stress me out except around finals. I get very excited to learn new things. I spend most of my day alone, either going to class or just hanging around campus. I enjoy the solitude and freedom that it entails. I don't have to ask if I'm allowed to go somewhere or anything, like I had to at home. 

The evening is when my mood tends to go down. Sometimes it stays fine, but when it doesn't, it definitely feels like depression, which I'm very familiar with. I've been on antidepressants for over 6 months and have gotten much better since arriving at college. The only time I feel down is evenings, typically triggered by some kind of interaction with my roommates. I have been friends with them since middle school, but sometimes they make me feel like the odd one out. I'm the only guy, I grew up with the most siblings, and I'm transgender. Also, they are both really into reading and are always talking about books. I wish I could enjoy reading, and sometimes I do, but it's very hard for me to focus on the page for long enough to actually finish it. Almost every night we do a crossword puzzle together, which can either be really fun or terrible. It turns terrible (triggers my depression) when something happens that makes me feel dumb, like I don't know an answer that is so obvious to both my roommates. 

Once I feel depressed like that, all I can do is lie in bed silently and listen to music, usually sad songs. I fall asleep and feel better in the morning.

name: Clare Murray
GenItems_narr:
overall, i think i typically am in a good mood, but often on days when i have an earlier class, which is twice a week, i will skip breakfast in order to sleep a little later, which can impact my mood in the mornings. I try to keep a balance between school work and free time so that i can stay on track with my classes but not feel too burnt out. to do this i like to keep a set schedule of when i do work for each class, which helps me focus and stay up do date, and i like having the consistency of a routine. 

in my free time, i like to read and spend time with my roommates. because my schoolwork has such a set routine to it, i leave my free time less structured and tend not to make too many strict plans. spend my weekends sleeping in, reading, and making plans day by day.

name: Tammy Wong
GenItems_narr:
There are certain periods when I become energetic in terms of everything, whether it be doing work or in a social environment. I believe it is because of hormones, but I am not sure. However, I solely believe that my mood during the day depends on how much sleep I get. I can get cranky one day and nice another day. Recently, I am excited to get up in the morning but I think it is because I am in an energetic period. Yet, I do find myself stressing over having the opportunity to hang out with friends. Thus, I try to become productive in school work. I have finished over a week's worth of schoolwork because of this nervous habit. I still find myself itching to get some work done. I usually find myself getting tired at the same time along with a certain schedule that my body follows. 

I get energetic with friends, but when something ruins my mood. I find myself becoming quiet or keeping up with a conversation. It is hard to focus when something is occupying my mind. However, this quiet period usually comes and goes. So I don't find myself down for a long period of time. This feeling does come back from time to time.
GenItems_Unique_item_1: cranky one day and nice another day

name: Fatima Rodriguez
GenItems_narr: At the moment I am person whole is going through the motions. I am a third year student here at UC Davis and I am majoring in Human Development. I currently work at Sweet and Shavery in downtown Davis. When I’m at work I’m casually happy, this is because I am a person who like to interact with people. I’m a social person with no social life. This is why I’m currently going through the motions of life. My first year of college was online line and because of this I wasn’t given the opportunity to make friends. My second year wasn’t the best either, my only friend was kicked out of college and as for making friends my third year, there has been no luck. I do have a boyfriend who makes me very happy. We are gonna make a year in May. We meet my first year of college in my home town. On the daily I go to school I’m the mornings and I’m the afternoons I go to work. Since I have no social life, when I’m not at school or work I’m in my apartment. At the moment I am going through a room change because my current roommates aren’t the best. So during the next few weeks I’m going to be moving into a new apartment which I am really looking forward to. I will finally get my own room for the first time ever and I will no longer be in a toxic environment. As for school, I am taking a pretty easy load this quarter so I won’t have much stress there. Work isn’t stressful either, it’s an ice cream shop so it’s relatively easy. My only problem is my room situation and hopefully that will be resolved soon. I am a first generation student and because this it has been a lot harder for me to find my way around college life. I don’t feel like I fit in in most places. This is also a big problem for me when it comes to making friends. A lot of students have parents that have once attended college and so they have people to guide them and give them pointers. I on other hand didn’t. I am also a Latina who is Catholic and is a great believer in family and there traditions. I grew up in Los Angeles and Davis is nothing like LA. I sometimes get homesick. I miss the food and the different traditions that I would do with my family. Overall over these next three weeks my emotions might be all over the place. Some days I might be happy and others I might just be going through the motions. I depends on who I’m with that day and what I’m doing.
GenItems_Unique_item_1: I am at my happiest when I am with my boyfriend
GenItems_Unique_item_2: Having a social life is important when it comes to my mood
GenItems_Unique_item_3: My roommate situation is very stressful and puts a damper on my mood
GenItems_Unique_item_4: I feel homesick and wish that theres was some places in Davis that resembled home
GenItems_Unique_item_5: Being a first generation student makes me feel like an outsider
GenItems_Unique_item_6: Having my first year of college online due to COVID was very difficult
GenItems_Unique_item_7: COVID interfered with my ability to make friends and have a social life
GenItems_Unique_item_8: My roommate situation makes me feel stressed out and helpless
GenItems_Unique_item_9: Dealing with my roommates put me in a bad mood and they make it a toxic environment
GenItems_Unique_item_10: My work environment makes me feel welcome and puts me in a great mood
GenItems_Unique_item_11: My college experience hasn’t been the best because I didn’t have anyone to show me around
GenItems_Unique_item_12: Having to learn everything first hand has been a great experience
GenItems_Unique_item_13: Making friends had been a great and meaningful experience for me
GenItems_Unique_item_14: On the daily I am someone who just goes through the motions of life
GenItems_Unique_item_15: Before college and COVID I was a much happier person
GenItems_Unique_item_16: COVID effected me in a lot more ways than I can explain
GenItems_Unique_item_17: My mood depends on who and what I am doing on that day
GenItems_Unique_item_18: I like being a first generation student and I like all of the experiences that come with it
GenItems_Unique_item_19: I have a great social life with a lot of friends
GenItems_Unique_item_20: Working and school are the only things that matter to me

name: Daphne Sandoval
GenItems_narr:
After finding out my younger sister has cancer my responsibilities went higher than before. Everyday is a constant struggle of who is going to take and pickup my other younger siblings from school. Because most of the time it is me who does this, my days are filled. In the morning I usually wake up to cloth and feed my siblings. When waking up in the morning my usual thoughts are about how tired I am and how I wish to sleep. This is likely because I stay up to do school work or other things and wake up early. Another important factor is that I get bad headaches majority of the time, so the first thing I do is take medicine. This makes me spiral into my thoughts in how I wished the doctors payed more attention to my problem, rather than giving up and just giving medicine to control it for the day. 
Once I have taken my siblings to school I go back home and prepare to go to school. Most of my thoughts during this time are about what could happen on the way there, which leads to many plan b’s. This is a cause of my anxiety which has led me to not do things out of my comfort zone, and driving has always been on the top. While driving too school it is one of the times my thoughts start to run wild. This could be things I need to do, or what I plan to do once I get home. The rest of the day I mostly do homework. Unlike other people I know I never go out because I for some reason don’t want to and would rather be in bed than talking to people. Once I go to bed this is when I really start to go deep into my thoughts. Not always but a lot of times I could be awake for 1-2 hours in just thinking. Most of my thoughts during this time are a result of my anxiety and so they are not pretty.

name: Kyle Walker
GenItems_narr: I have a well-designed time table to follow. I got up early in the morning and say my  prayer. Then I go out for a walk in the open air and walk for half an hour. Then I come back home and have my breakfast.
GenItems_Unique_item_5: I have a well designed time table to follow

name: Sicily Brancatelli
GenItems_narr:
Recently I’ve been craving a healthier life style. I feel as if this will make me happier and bring my life more balance. I’ve recently started drinking 2 liters of water a day, incorporating at least one bowl of fruit into my diet, and began going to the gym at 8 pm everyday. I’m very proud of myself recently as I feel I’ve grown more productive. I recently applied for EBT and I even go out of my way to complete research studies for money. 
    Coming as a first generational student from a low income family, this is progress. My whole life I have been so used to pushing my health aside and so with this I feel free. I finally have time for myself and self-care which drastically helps my mood. Not only that, I’ve been practicing time management and am currently academically thriving. I would say that my life is pretty great at this moment.

name: Aaron Becerra
GenItems_narr:
I sometimes feel lonely. I haven't really met any other students who are Mexican or Latino. I guess that's why I also feel out of place here. My hometown had a completely different demographic that it really does sometimes make me feel homesick. I try and talk to my friends at least every day or every other day but, I know that they also have their own lives and are busy. I don't want to be too much of a bother but it does make me feel so much better when I talk to them. 
     Another thing that kind of bothers me is how tired I usually am. I try and get 8 hours of sleep every night yet I still feel tired. I'm not quite sure why this happens. Perhaps I'm not getting the proper nutrients to keep me energetic. Everyday from around 6-8 pm I want to take a fat nap.
     I am going to try and join some clubs and organizations to see which ones I like and can make new friends.

name: Roxanna Restrepo
GenItems_narr: On a daily basis I study, and go out on walks. Most days, I don’t feel motivated. I have to force myself to do what I have to do because otherwise I’ll get very bad anxiety. I used to exercise, but I have to catch up on notes in my classes. I want to practice journaling my thoughts as I am prone to overthinking. I overthink about many things. My relationships, my grades, my appearance, what I ate, etc. I am anxious most days and I try my best to relax and take things slowly. It can be very difficult as I don’t have a therapist anymore. I am trying my best. Being a student takes a toll mentally on me. I think what keeps me going is the pressure I place upon myself. I tell myself that the better I do the more of a reward I will get later on in life. Essentially, I put myself on a pedestal so I that I can achieve the best possible outcome in school and in life. I keep going because I have to.

name: Danielle Koay
GenItems_narr:
Usually, I am a pretty positive person who enjoys much of my day. I look forward to meal times at the dining commons so that I could talk with my friends and eat. The past week, I have been either going to the gym, rock climbing, or dancing daily; sometimes in the early morning at 8AM. I feel that exercising and getting my body moving really helps get my mood up and makes me feel even better. I enjoy bike rides to class as well.

When I'm in class, I find it hard to pay attention and listen to my professors. I tend to get my work done, though, and I feel satisfied when I get things checked off in Canvas. I do look forward to my math class, because my Professor sounds like Gru from Despicable Me. I find he is also a very good Professor. Other lectures, however, are quite boring to me.

I have clubs that I look forward to on Mondays and Fridays; both being Christian club. I am working on growing in my faith.

name: Christa Chapman
GenItems_narr:
Most days I am am in a good mood and ready to get through all of my tasks for the day. School In general makes me tired and stressed often. I live off campus so getting to school is stressful and often anxiety inducing when the bus is late. Also my classes this quarter are pretty early in the morning, so that leads to being tired throughout the day. I also have a heavier work load so I am staying up later and still waking up early so again tiredness is a constant theme. I don't have classes on Fridays which is nice so it's a good break from school , so that makes me happy. I usually work part time a few days a week and I like my job, it involves kids so I usually leave happy, but physically tired because of all of the standing. Whenever I call my family I am happy, and tend to be in a high happier mood than normal. 

My roommate is fun to be around, I feel comfortable and safe with her. I don't feel as safe or comfortable with my housemates, it's a little more like walking on thin ice and trying to not make anyone mad. Some times certain of my house mates makes me mad and angry when they do or tell me dumb stuff. In one of my clubs I feel safe  and comfortable and free to be myself. Sometimes in class when I don't understand the class content and it seems like everyone else does I often feel like I don't belong in college at all because I'm not smart enough for it. When the bus is late is tied to get anxious and frustrated. When people leave the kitchen at my apartment a mess I am also mad. I tend to get tired like an hour into my classes because my attention span gets less and less, probably cause im tired.
GenItems_Unique_item_2: ready for the day and week
GenItems_Unique_item_3: school makes me tired and stressed
GenItems_Unique_item_13: free to be myself in my club
GenItems_Unique_item_14: don't feel like I belong in school sometimes

name: Megan Nguyen
GenItems_narr:
Most days I feel apathetic; I don't get excited to go to classes, but I also don't dread it. I feel like my college life is very mundane, but I also enjoy schedules and regularity, so I can't complain. 
I go home almost every weekend because my parents expect me to, and I feel like I owe them for everything they've done and that it would be disrespectful and disappointing if I didn't.
I used to take naps frequently throughout the week, but it doesn't work with my schedule this quarter and instead I end up falling asleep during all my classes, especially on Tuesdays and Thursdays which have three classes back to back from 10 am to 3 pm.

name: Itzel Rodriguez Santos
GenItems_narr:
Everyday I wake up around 9 to commute to campus and attend class. I usually feel tired when waking because I tend to go to bed late. After my 10 am class, on Monday’s, Tuesdays, and Fridays, I immediately go back home to go to work from 11:30am until 4:30pm. On those days I have two other class in the evening but since the lectures are recorded I end up not attending in person unless there’s a midterm or quiz. On Tuesdays and thursdays I have two classes and then spend a few hours writing notes and doing homework. Sometimes I feel like there isn’t enough time in a day for me to be able to relax and do things that I enjoy that aren’t school related. That’s one if the reasons I think I sleep late because it gives me more time to read books or watch shows I like. 
I think I’m really lucky to have the job that I have right now, my boss is really nice and is flexible with my school schedule. It’s in an HR office and sometimes I do feel like I’m not doing enough there because I don’t have a specific job that needs to be done everyday so sometimes I’m just sitting trying to look somewhat busy. After work I’ll sometimes try to hangout with friends but they also work and it’s hard to match up schedules to hangout all together. then of course i still have homework to finish when I get home so even when I’m out it’s still in the back of mind. I’ll also hangout with my sister because we like the same things and don’t mind doing things together but separately.

name: Melanie Born
GenItems_narr:
I typically am not a morning person and like to wake up around 9-10 am. However, I have a 10 am class on Mondays and Wednesdays that I can't miss so I have to get up around 8:30 am. I like to stay in bed for a while in the mornings and typically I'll go on my phone and use social media or entertainment apps like YouTube or Twitter. On weekends, sometimes I don't get out of bed until 11-12. On days when I have an early class that's recorded and attendance isn't mandatory, I find myself waking up at the right time and debating whether I should actually go, usually based on how tired I feel. If I feel too tired, I often will go back to sleep for a few hours. My morning routine always consists of breakfast and coffee (I'm really into making coffee). I'm usually excited about making coffee but less excited about making breakfast. I don't have the energy or motivation in the mornings to make something that takes a lot of effort so I typically eat whatever seems the easiest at the time. During all of my meals, I enjoy watching a YouTube video, usually about whatever obsession I'm into at the time. 
After breakfast, I try to remember to take my anxiety meds (5mg of Lexapro) and an allergy pill if it feels like I need it. Then, if I need to go out, I will, and if I don't need to go out then I look at whatever I need to get done and try to be productive until I need to go out. If I don't have anything to do that day or don't need to go out, I usually stay home all day and just play games, hang out with friends on discord, or watch YouTube/Netflix/etc. Sometimes I crave boba or fast food, though, and so in those instances, I'll go out (either biking or walking depending on my energy levels and the distance I need to travel) and I'll either bring it back to my apartment or just eat it there (typically alone). I do a lot of activities alone unless I make plans with friends or run into a roommate. I think I just enjoy doing activities alone because I can control exactly what I do and how I do it. I also consider myself an introvert and need alone time to recharge. However, I do enjoy hanging out with people because it gets lonely unless I do. 
Lately, I've been trying to become more healthy. I think about my food options a lot more than I used to and typically try my best to have a good balance of foods. I love sweet treats though so I typically will have at least 1 per day even if I know I probably shouldn't. For lunch, I typically have more energy than in the morning so if I have enough energy/motivation I'll actually cook something. I am not the biggest fan of cooking so I typically need a good amount of motivation to cook something. Otherwise, I'll microwave some leftovers or if I'm out and about I'll buy something from campus stores or downtown. 
When it comes to my anxiety,  I typically feel the most anxious in my classes, especially if it's a class where I am required to talk. For me, anxiety is more about overthinking things than anything and wanting to present to the world as relatively likable and normal. I think about the noises I make, whether I'm being too loud doing certain actions, whether it would it be weird to drink water/coffee right now, if I pull down my mask to drink do I have anything on my face that people would find gross, if I raise my hand will I get it wrong or say something dumb, do I smell bad and can people around me smell me, and things of that nature. After a hangout with someone, especially if I really want them to like me, I think about all the things I've done during the hangout and think about whether it was weird or rude. All of these thoughts go for texting and social media, too. 
Afternoons typically go one of two ways: I either have the motivation to get my work done or I don't have the motivation and slack off (social media, sudoku puzzles, YouTube/Netflix/etc). If I get my work done in the afternoon then in the evenings I watch YouTube or do something else I find fun until I have to shower and go to bed. If I don't get my work done in the afternoon then I get it done in the evenings instead and then call it a night. I typically only do what is required though and I don't usually get much of a headstart on things unless it's supposed to be a busier week. Regardless, though, I always eat dinner. Whether I actually cook or just microwave again depends on my energy/motivation levels. 
Finally, before bed, I typically will browse things on my phone because I think I'm a bit addicted to my devices. I sometimes go on Twitter which I usually regret because I spend way too much time on it. I do it anyway because it's addicting, though, and I have a fear of missing out. YouTube is usually just entertaining too but the shorts are very addictive too. Then, I go to sleep once I either realize I need to or whenever I feel sufficiently sleepy. Typically, I sleep between 11 and 1 am.
GenItems_Unique_item_1: I feel motivated to go to morning classes
GenItems_Unique_item_2: I feel motivated to make coffee
GenItems_Unique_item_3: I feel motivated to cook for breakfast
GenItems_Unique_item_4: I feel tired or like I need more sleep
GenItems_Unique_item_5: I was anxious in my most recent class
GenItems_Unique_item_6: I feel motivated to cook lunch
GenItems_Unique_item_7: I feel motivated to do work before lunch
GenItems_Unique_item_8: I feel motivated to do work between lunch and dinner
GenItems_Unique_item_9: I feel motivated to do work after dinner
GenItems_Unique_item_10: I feel motivated to cook dinner
GenItems_Unique_item_11: I was anxious during my most recent interaction with someone

name: Meg Shieh
GenItems_narr:
I'm usually very energetic, but I get tired after lunch (if I eat lunch). I feel like it signals that it's nearing the end of the day for me, so my productivity just drops. If I don't eat lunch and keep working through the day, then the lack of breaks in between helps me stay focused.

I'm usually pretty excited about my work, but there are definitely days where I am just so over it. I feel like Tuesdays and Thursdays are my most productive days because Mondays are just after the weekend, Wednesdays are midweek, and Fridays are just before the weekend.

name: Tara Khan
GenItems_narr:
I live in an apartment in Sacramento with my partner, and we moved here from Pakistan in August. My daily life involves driving to school from Sacramento around four times a week (Monday through Thursday), spending time on campus, driving home, house chores like cooking and cleaning, and spending time with my partner. On Mondays and Wednesdays, I have long days at school (around 10 hours, ending at 8pm) and that takes up most of my time. I enjoy those days as I get to see my friends and peers, but I run out of energy towards the end of the day as I don't get to go home and decompress. On those days, I also make sure to pack lots of food and snacks because I get hungry every couple of hours. I would say that my mood is totally dependent on my body, as it is heavily affected by how hungry or sleepy I am. I get home quite late on those days and my partner usually makes dinner so that it's ready by the time I come home. I eat and usually spend time with my partner by watching tv, playing music together (guitar/piano/sing), and/or smoking weed. On Tuesdays and Thursdays, I have class in the morning and I either stay on campus or go home depending on whether I have stuff to do at home, haven't eaten, or whether I need to stay on campus and do homework. On these days I only have class in the mornings, my partner and I sometimes go for walks in the evening. These are also the days when I have time to call my family. Due to the time difference, I have to call them in the morning or the night. Calling family and friends recharges me, as I'm very close to my sisters, parents, and long-distance friends. I'm not a morning person and I find it hard to wake myself up in the mornings, but I have to get up around 8am four times a week (very early for me) due to my morning classes. In order to wake up, I always have chai in the mornings, and I never miss breakfast. I try to have eggs in the morning but if I'm feeling lazy I'll have toast with a spread or cereal. My partner and I cook most of our food for lunch and dinner, and we like to vary what we eat as we get bored of meals easily. 
Friday to Sunday are very flexible days. I have homework to do as well as life admin things like groceries and house chores, and I also like to go for drives, road trips, or meet my friends during the weekend. This is also the time I get organised for the upcoming week. I am organised and use my planner a lot, but I also struggle with motivating myself to work and end up procrastinating a lot. I know all the things I have to do (I like making lists) but I don't usually get all of it done and end up scrambling at the last minute. I like routine, but I don't like planning my day down to the hour – I prefer making lists of the things I want to accomplish in a day and try to get through those things at my own pace. I struggle with establishing a set routine for myself in the morning, but whenever I manage to do it, I always benefit from it. I am an extrovert and feel recharged when I spend time with friends and peers, but I also love staying in my house in my PJs. I have a lot of hobbies but I spend a lot more time than I would like scrolling on my phone or lounging on the couch, which I feel prevents me from pursuing hobbies of mine like singing/performing, gardening, and getting involved in activities at school.

name: Addison U
GenItems_narr:
On any usual day, I'd wake up, this quarter around 8-9 am. I'd feel tired but quickly get up, get changed, and prepare to head out. I'm usually anxious, as is always whenever I'm in between classes so I get up an hour early and leave 30 minutes before, whether that makes me 20min early or not doesn't really matter since I'd rather be super early than panic being late. During class, I'd be either very interested or extremely bored (i.e., in Chem and Math I'd be scribbling down notes but in Psyc(coincidentally) I'd be playing chess or Bloons TD 6 whenever my prof starts to go on a tangent and/or is going over already learned concepts). By the end of my classes, I'd be very tired and I'll be thinking of food, either at the DC or out at local restaurants or getting boba as a treat. I'd go back and nap or binge-watch something (youtube, tv show, twitch) and talk to my friends if they are online on discord or messages. I'd continue this until dinner and probably get some homework done before I shower and feel tired enough to sleep. 

Throughout the day I'd get really annoyed at random things like people walking VERY slowly, people in lecture asking really lengthy and irrelevant questions, or just being uncomfortable after a long, sweaty walk to class. On many occasions though, I'd find myself dealing with having crohn's and the symptoms that come with it (i.e, pain and toilet) which is probably why I'm tired as it also makes me struggle to get any decent sleep. When I get the chance to sit with my thoughts I'd probably think about how I am not doing as well academically as I did in high school or how this next exam is not gonna go well. Some other thoughts are feeling out of place (constantly wonder how I even got into Davis) or just feeling like I'm not going to make it through (well, graduate yes but not with any decent GPA or experiences to put on my resume). 

Other than my thoughts some stuff does come up and give my days a little bit of sparkle. Sometimes my friends start talking about certain topics and it annoys me a little (especially a friend that goes to UC Santa Cruz). Mostly because he's a friend that doesn't really know how it is to struggle financially and it annoys me that he thinks showing himself paying off tuition with his parent's money or that his sister randomly sent him $200 is cool. Otherwise, it's nice to talk to them and watch them play video games (unless I'm home then I'd join but I currently don't have a PC at the res hall)Another frequent but not daily event would be one of my friends asking me for academic help. We've been working on our assignments together since high school and it's nice to be able to catch up and laugh while we help each other with assignments, especially because her classes are in line with mine. I've also been talking to another student at Davis and I think we're getting along nicely so that has brightened up my day whenever we get a good conversation started.  Finally, I do keep in contact with my parents but that's usually kept to when I'm going to visit home, my mother inquiring about my day, or playing the role of tech & English support. Typical Asian-fist gen child responsibilities and experiences.

name: Janni Lin
GenItems_narr:
In a few weeks, I'll be starting a new job, so I think my mood and everyday activities will be quite different. My current job has been a source of stress and frustration for a while, so I don't feel super happy to go to work. However, I'm happy that I've quit and I am glad to have a new opportunity elsewhere. I think I may be a bit stressed when I start my new job, as I'll feel pressure to perform and to be happier here than I was previously. I'll also be around new groups of people, which tends to overwhelm me. I get very quiet and then feel guilty for being quiet, and think that people will judge me and stereotype me. 
In general, my beliefs are that people should be competent and also intelligent enough to think for themselves. I sometimes find it annoying when people are not self-aware or when they base their entire personalities around pleasing others. 
My personality is quite calm, and I'm diligent and always follow through on what I say I will do. I never make impulsive decisions and am loyal to my friends.

name: Jasmine Bucago
GenItems_narr:
I guess we'll start with school. My whole life I've been pushed in a direction to go to medical school or something in the medical field, so I've been always preparing for the NPB major here at Davis, however, I tried the classes my first quarter as a transfer in fall '22 and it really took a toll on my mental health. I pretty much felt very directionless and very scared for my future because the classes weren't sustainable and I didn't really have any other job prospects that I thought about or wanted to go into. I still have those thoughts but I'm just trying to take the steps I can right now to explore and see what fits me best. 

I decided to stay in my declared major as a cognitive science w/ emphasis in neuroscience major. This is the first quarter that I'm taking classes for it and I can say that I like them but its very different and not so much stem-like so it feels like it's too easy but I'm also not really studying as much as I should because while the material itself isn't hard its a lot of content. I'm not really sure where I'm going with this major but I'm just going with the flow. 

This quarter I only have one class period at 8am which is just on wednesdays and is honestly nice because I don't have to wake up at 6 like  I had to last quarter. I really screwed up my sleep schedule all of last year so its been really hard trying to fix it. So even with my other classes starting at 9am I still find myself going to bed late at night, like 1-2 and waking up at 7 or 7:30 if I want more sleep, but either way I feel like I don't utilize my time good enough and end up not being able to eat breakfast or just really quickly shoving a granola/belvita bar down. Which isn't really satisfying because I'm still hungry. Another thing that I discovered is that though I'm not clinically diagnosed, I feel like I have ADHD because I struggle with procrastination, frequent moving around (nothing crazy but enough to the point where I feel like I'm scratching myself too much or changing my seating position a lot), starting one thing and easily getting distracted with another task and I have to constantly check myself or ask myself "hold on why are we here and not doing that other thing". I also have days where I'm really productive and knock things out and then times where I just wait until the last minute and rush, or just waste my time on social media and feel guilty about it at the same time. 

I feel like I'm pretty in tune with my emotions and how I feel day to day, though I haven't really been thinking about it. BUT I will say that a little over a week ago I just started content creating and I'm mainly doing it for monetization, so theres this pressure to try and learn all these marketing strategies and how to use hooks to draw peoples attention as well as come up with new content multiple times a day so my brain feels like its on the go all the time and that I need to be distracted by something to feel present. I talked about this with my roommate the other day and after I feel better and re-evaluated how I'm going to go about content creating and maybe not posting so much. It's just very competitive on social media now so everyone is fighting to be seen. I'm not doing it for the fame aspect, in fact I get paranoid about putting my face out on the internet just because of all the creepy people so I'm not even sure if I should keep making videos. I'm just trying to grow so I can eventually get paid and I guess feel like people actually enjoy and engage with my content. I also feel guilty because I'm contributing to platforms that people are sucked into and addicted to, and I feel selfish for adding to that fire just so I can get paid. But I do want to make sure that at least my content is enjoyable but educational at the same time so I don't know. 

I have a roommate that I love, but because of her past experiences with guys, especially white guys, she seems to be very hyper aware of racism and sexism. Especially towards white people. (she's korean/white). She was talking to me about a problem she was having with her friend/classmate, and though she found out that her classmate had bipolar disorder which contributed to the problems they were having and the behaviors that were exerted to my roommate, she combined the disorder along with "because she's white, she was acting that way because she was expressing that feeling of oppression" or something along those lines and I don't know it just bothers me the way she talks about her views towards caucasian people. all of my childhood friends were white and I never felt any sort of oppression against them. I think I do subconsciously feel some sort of power dynamic by being asian and feeling lesser of SOME sort but I never really thought about it. I would never bring another person down just because of the color of their skin. To call someone a "boring, white guy" and that I should date someone else, or to call someone a sexist pig just because a guy talked to other guys and not the girls in a group(because maybe hes just more comfortable with the same gender which is pretty normal). Calling someone a misogynist and saying they hate all men and overall just being hateful. I don't know its just been frustrating. 

Because I get overwhelmed when I have more than a couple of tasks, regardless of how big or small the task is, I've learned to write everything down on a list so its easier for my brain to process it. I'm trying to learn how to set a realistic goal of tasks to finish throughout the day, and sometimes I feel accomplished but sometimes I feel like I didn't do enough or I didn't get something more important out of the way. 

I don't feel like i have the best diet right now, I try to eat vegetables when I can but sometimes I'll just wait or not utilize my time in a responsible way until I'm too hungry then I'll just put random things together and I don't really space out time to cook a proper meal. I get pretty lazy because of this and I'd like to have meals prepared for school so I don't have to go back and forth but I just don't feel as organized as I should be. 

I realized that I used to involuntarily judge and critique and assume things about other people and I also was really hard on myself before. I've learned to become more aware of how I'm feeling, why I'm feeling certain ways, and to also catch myself when I'm being unnecessarily judgemental towards others. I do a lot of mental checks. 

I surround myself with pretty good friends. I used to have a lot of one sided friendships growing up and didn't really know that I would be able to have the friends I do now. They're attentive, funny, easygoing and caring and we support each other and its really nice. I like to think that I have good intuition most times.

Sorry for the long submission, I hope I wasn't too all over the place :)

name: Jennifer Vega
GenItems_narr:
My every day as a UC Davis student prominently involves reading and going to class and any free time involves listening to music. For every day, I have a list of assignments and any tasks I wan to get done in my phone notes app. I am very diligent about the list and view it multiple times a day. I love my psychology major classes but sometimes feel overwhelmed with all the required reading material. I find that when I read the textbook for my abnormal psychology class, I sometimes get restless and lose concentration pretty quickly, which leads me to spend excessive amounts of time on a single chapter. However reading the textbook for my developmental psychology class feels like entertainment, I find myself genuinely intrigued by what the next sentence will reveal.
Some days I will look around and feel like I am behind in comparison to my peers as I hear and see about their achievements. I go through every day hoping to find out more about the direction of my future. I don't have a plan for after graduation or even a career of interest. However, this school year I have begun to get a sense of direction by taking developmental psychology courses. As of now, I am interested in learning about infants and their perceptions. I assume that is why I enjoy the reading material for the respective course and find it more engaging than any of my other courses.
Every other day I run into my one close friend here at Davis. I do spend most of my time on my own so running into him or making plans with him is always a very enjoyable change of pace. As a minority in Davis, it is very nice to have someone from my home city and of the same cultural background to discuss the joys and hardships of college life.
When I sit in my dorm room and feel unable to do any work and any other task seems unappealing, I like to grab a sketchbook and draw or scribble on it. In all aspects of daily life, I overthink and try to perfect but lately, I have been trying to fight that with my drawings. I try to draw on impulse and not care much about messy lines, I intentionally make the drawing chaotic and messy.
I think I tend to be a little on the anxious side and tend to overthink anything and everything. I think of all possible wrong outcomes and consider the unlikely bad outcomes. 
I visit the arboretum on campus on some weekends and go for bike rides around it. This is one of my favorite things to do at Davis and it gives me great euphoria. Listening to music while at the arboretum is always a pick me up even for times when I feel homesick.
I was raised catholic, but around middle school, I stopped going to church and practicing the religion as much. However, I recently reverted to praying every night before bed and I feel that it helps me be in a constant state of calm and feel centered for the next day to come.

name: Grace Anderegg
GenItems_narr:
Most days I spend my time just relaxing and talking with my roommates. I feel like I should engage more with my peers in Davis, but I genuinely really enjoy the people I'm living with and I met them as friends last year. I struggle with branching out because I have a low social battery. I also keep in touch with a lot of my high school friends and we enjoy playing video games together. One of the things I struggled with since coming here was my change of identity. In high school, I identified with being a student-athlete and working out more. Since then, I have had a difficult time kind of getting myself hyped up, but when I do go I enjoy it. However, since going to college, I have also been able to explore cooking and learn how to make more complex meals. 

One thing that's impacted my perception of my daily life would probably be the fact that I'm adopted, so people's experiences with their parents are very different when we talk about it. I think that my parents and I have a relatively good relationship and communication because we've been a bit more open. I also think that the more open communication with my parents has helped me communicate emotionally better with friends and be more aware of other people's feelings as well as being more emotionally mature than others. 

In my roommate situation, there is one person that I do not like because they are rude and don't consider others (i.e cleaning and being loud when others are sleeping). This somewhat impacts my daily life because I attempt to avoid them when I can. They tend to crave male validation, so it's hard to be friends with them when they seem to compete. Although, it's weird because I am in a relationship and they are, but they compete with our mutual male friends who are also in relationships. All of this has created drama within the apartment which I think in general is not healthy.

name: McKenzie Dinehart
GenItems_narr: Typically my classes start later so I am pretty energized when I wake up. The gym is what motivates me to get out of bed and I am usually very awake the whole day. When my first class starts I am always really focused by get less as the class goes on. I get distracted pretty easily when I am uninterested. I find myself liking my lab and discussion classes because they are so small and I have to interact with strangers, I would say I am a pretty nervous speaker. On Tuesdays and Thursday I am tired because my labs end really late. The first thing I do when I get back is get food from the dinning commons which gives me enough energy to start studying. Compared to last quarter I am pretty happy with my life/ routine in Davis. Before I missed my home and family a lot. I am from San Diego am everything I love about the city is not in Davis. I also really heavily on the support from my friends and family which was hard to find here. I love socializing with my friends that I made here however it does annoy me that we often make plans that like almost never happen. My roommate is my best friend who I have known since I was 7 and she is always someone I can rely on but I sometimes if feels like she wants us to have the same friends and do the same stuff and I am really trying to find some distance for us to have our own lives. Chemistry is a really frustrating class for me because when I think I understand a concept well, I usually do not. Something that usually brightens my mood is talking to my boyfriend, who is going to college in San Diego. Sometimes when we talk though things feel off and then that leads to me overthinking.

name: Gillian Fong
GenItems_narr:
I am starting to feel a bit overwhelmed as I will be graduating soon. I'm still not sure what career I want to pursue. I am considering physical therapy right now, and am spending this quarter interning at a clinic. I also have to wake up early, which is something I'm not used to. Initially, I thought I would dread waking up. Surprisingly, I actually like working the morning shift as I feel very productive getting things done earlier.
I travel back home on the weekends sometimes because I miss my family. I enjoy spending time with them, but it also leads me to miss out on everything happening in Davis.

name: Eduardo Flores
GenItems_narr: I am very high energy most of the time, except when I got to Davis, where I started feeling tired from school. I transferred from a community college where they were on a semester system and I remained on top of my school work. I managed time very well and I succeeded in building relationships with professors and fellow students. Once I got to Davis, I struggled to adapt to the 10-week quarters and found it hard to stay afloat on schoolwork sometimes. I didn't let it get to me too much because I prioritized having some fun exercising or seeing people I met on the weekends. I also had such an awakening and some things that people don't talk about. I noticed really offputting things here at school. For one, the professors literally don't care about the students for the most part and many of them can't teach to save their own lives. They are hired as researchers and have no experience teaching people. I get it they try, but they cannot expect students to get things in one week. An elementary school teacher can do a better job than more than half of these professors. Another thing I noticed is the number of people who really care about school. I know there isn't a true way of measuring how much one cares about things, but when it comes to school, people just lack the drive to be true students. Time and time again I see cheating and dishonesty in the classroom that oftentimes lands them better grades than mine. I take pride in my mistakes and failures because I did so organically and without the help of online sources. Students literally show up and don't pay attention in class. Students come here with 4.0 and above GPAs and don't know common knowledge. I don't worry about other people as much because it is just a waste of energy. I believe the pandemic brought to light the oddness of people. I am very social and I enjoy being in public with people. I really struggled to make connections with fellow students for the past year and believe me I have tried. I have a very busy schedule, but I have time to play recreational soccer and go out with my girlfriend. So many attempts at friendship have sunk and the ones that I have encountered fizzled out due to a lack of communication or just a disconnection in vibe. When I moved out to Davis from Southern California, I really enjoyed being by myself in a new world. It wasn't the first time I have been far away from family for a long time as I have studied abroad in community college and for travel soccer. Calls or facetime with my family really help me get through the struggles I have faced with the reality of how people are. Not everyone is so nice and genuinely caring as I found out the hard way. There are nice people out there and people who share qualities like mine, I just have yet to find them. Mentally I am strong as I don't suffer from anything and am good about bouncing back from setbacks. I have always been like this all throughout my life, being able to be okay and lighten the mood with myself when things don't go the way I wanted. My schedule has been really busy since coming here and I really want to go to the gym more, but haven't properly made time to go. I am a bit insecure about how thin I am and have the goal to gain a few pounds. I think the exhaustion from the day gives me excuses not to go. Whenever I do go, I feel amazing and good about myself. I currently am striving to get a schedule to go to the gym more sorted out. I also find it interesting how people grow up after meeting people here at Davis. Not everyone has their upbringing bad, but the majority of people I have met have had some sort of trauma in their lives that affected the way they are. I'm not talking about trauma from a death of a loved one but from some sort of abuse either mentally or physically. Yet, they talk about it like it's nothing or its normal, which frightens me a bit when I hear it. Overall, I have my appetite, my health is good, I got a loving and supportive family back home, and a drive to get my school done. I feel like I owe no one nothing and I can accomplish the hardships that lie ahead.

name: Pralisha Kansakar
GenItems_narr:
My life is pretty boring most days with college 9-4 Monday-Friday. I happily await for weekend each week for some rest time. But weekends too tend to be hectic with either family functions or assignment deadlines. I find it hard to have some free time for me. When I do have some free time, I watch some series to relax myself. I am also fond of painting and engage myself in some creative work whenever I get time. 

The highlight of my day is spending some time with my dog, who needs to be spoon fed cause she's pampered. I also enjoy the daily dinner session with my family, where we share the events of each of our day and bond as a family. I do not necessarily like outdoor functions unless it is with my small close group of friends. I feel my energy at the end of the day when I attend the university. And on off days, I feel guilty if i do not do something productive.

name: Bhavya Narang
GenItems_narr:
Hi, 
Please add 91 before messaging and you can use whatsApp to message. Since I'm not in US right now. 

I feel energetic at night and very lazy around morning and afternoon. I'm very much in my own thoughts these days. I'm confused about where should I pursue my higher studies. Some things worry me but sometimes I let things slide out but when imma alone it affects. 

During my office hours I feel good. I'm busy so my mind just thinks about doing work and finishing it soon.
GenItems_Unique_item_9: I am more involved in my
GenItems_Unique_item_10: Office work and think about finishing it quickly

name: Christine Nguyen
GenItems_narr: When I do not have school, such as during winter break, I tend to be a lot more healthy. I eat and sleep more regularly, whereas during school, I tend to become nocturnal and get around five hours of sleep usually. Because I am so tired from the lack of sleep, I often lack the energy to make myself food, resulting in me lying in bed for hours, unable to get up from how drained I am. This lack of energy also translates to schoolwork: I lack the energy and motivation to attend lectures and do my homework. Of course, as a perfectionist and eldest daughter of immigrants, I find these tasks daunting and the need to do everything perfectly, which means I get scared to begin anything I feel I can't do perfectly.
