When I see people in large groups around campus, it makes me sad because I'm socially anxious, and I feel like I don't have the capabilities to make friends out of my comfort zone. Whenever I'm with people I don't know well, such as on the weekends, I typically feel uncomfortable and want to go back to my room so I can isolate myself.

I am also very sensitive to sensory stimuli. I am able to focus well when I am in the right environment, but if I am studying in a loud and busy area, I cannot get anything done because the sounds overwhelm me. Even when I'm in a room and two of my friends are talking at the same time, I get frustrated with them. I'm also a very sensitive person and cry frequently when things affect me emotionally. I feel like I am very empathetic, so when something bad happens to my friend, I get almost as distressed as they are.

Right now, I am not liking my physiology course because the professor doesn't explain the concepts in a way that I understand. My discussion classes also feel a bit unnecessary, so I haven't really been enjoying those either. My classes in general just feel like more of a drag than they did before. I can't tell why, because they're actually easier than my classes last quarter. Everyone around me seems to be very sad too and it's affecting how I feel about my life.

Though I am relatively new to college, I am already worrying about getting into graduate school, as I know it can be very competitive. I feel like I have to get the perfect grades and do as much as I possibly can so I am a good candidate. I'm starting two jobs currently and I'm not sure how I'll be able to balance everything. I'm waiting it out to see if I need to quit one of them, but I know I will also feel guilty if I do quit, even if it's for the sake of my mental health. I worked so hard for both of the positions and my friends and family are very proud of my achievements so early into my college career, so I don't want to let them down.

name: Erica Lee
GenItems_narr:
I'm taking a full load of classes, and I try to go to all of them, but I already feel tempted to just watch the recordings. One of my current classes is really interesting to me, and I really like it. The other ones, I am still interested in, but less so. I work at the Coffee House,  usually around 14 hours per week, in a front of the house position. I'm also a member of the Mental Health Initiative, and I volunteer at a psychology lab somewhat informally. I just started volunteering as a staff member for one of the ASUCD Senators. 
This quarter, I've been spending most of the day on campus attending classes, working, and studying. I like being busy, but at the beginning of the quarter, I was already feeling kind of burned out. I do tend to struggle with burnout, even though I usually still feel like I'm not doing enough. I think I definitely do struggle with toxic productivity, feeling like I need to be doing something productive at all times. I still feel internal pressure to get involved in more activities, too, even though if I think about it, I'm doing plenty of things. But I feel like I should apply for more jobs, internships, research positions, volunteer positions, etc. I tend to compare how busy I am with other people, which I think is problematic. And when I have a lot of free time, I don't know what to do with it. I struggle to let myself take breaks and relax.
I used to do all the reading for my classes, but it's week 3, and I've already stopped doing some of it. I feel less motivated to do things, in general, if I don't have to.
I do really love my high school friends, and I usually have fun hanging out with them. I try to make time to hang out with my friends, but it can be hard to coordinate schedules, and I think I see them less this year than I used to before. It seems like we're all busier. I do feel lonely sometimes, especially when I spend large chunks of time on my own. I also tend to worry about whether my friends actually like me, especially because it feels like I'm the one initiating plans a lot of the time. But if I spend too much time alone, I will get sad and lonely, and sometimes that's a problem on the weekends. I also miss my family. I don't live that far away from home, so I can go home on the weekends, but I am close with them, and it's kind of hard living up in Davis without them. Especially after winter break, I got really used to being able to talk to them whenever and spending a lot of time with them. I find myself still missing winter break a lot because it was a really good time for me when I got to truly relax, have fun, and hang out with my high school friends, who I have trouble keeping in contact with now. 
I live with 3 other people in an apartment. Lately, I haven't been talking with them very much. I was friends with two of them before we decided to live together and honestly, I don't think I'm very good at living with other people. I would have preferred to have my own room, but my parents pay for my rent, and I didn't want to make them pay more, so I tried to make my rent as cheap as I could. I feel resentment towards my roommates sometimes. I don't think it's really justified, and it's usually about little things. I don't really bring it up. I've kind of just been keeping to myself at the apartment. My roommates are usually busy with their own things anyway. But I think living together has actually made our relationships somewhat worse. I was afraid of this last year, actually. Last year, when I was a freshman, I didn't talk much with my roommate either (a different person), and I felt similar feelings toward her. So maybe I'm just not very good at living with other people. I also feel like a bad roommate sometimes for not doing enough in terms of cleaning & stuff.
I think I'm an insecure person, and I worry considerably about what other people think about me. Oftentimes, I feel like I'm not funny or witty enough for other people to like me. I also feel insecure about my appearance sometimes. I think I'm also a pretty anxious person. I worry about a lot of things, and I think I have for a while. Oftentimes, I think that the things I worry about aren't even worth worrying about, but I can't stop worrying about them anyway. Like, they don't matter, but it feels like I need to be worrying about something. I used to worry a lot about food and exercise, and I felt like I may have had orthorexia, but I never talked about it with anyone, and it's been getting better lately. But I think that's because my anxiety has just shifted to worrying about other things. I wonder sometimes if I have an anxiety disorder, but I've never actually been diagnosed with a mental illness. I don't think it looks like it on the outside. I think I function well enough. I definitely do care about my grades, and I do enough to get As in my classes. But internally, I do worry a lot. I've also wondered if I have depression, but again, I haven't really seen anyone about that. I do feel tired a lot and not very motivated, but it's kind of normal for me. I think it gets worse when I'm by myself. I tend to feel a lot happier when I'm with other people and somewhat forget about my worries. It's a bit ironic because I'm participating in mental health advocacy and such, but I'm still not really taking care of or addressing my own mental health issues. So I feel like a hypocrite sometimes.
I also feel insecure because I haven't really decided on what career I want after college, and I hate when people ask me what I want to do. It always feels bad when I have to say that I don't really know yet, especially when other people already do know. I feel like I have a lot of interests, and it's hard for me to pick a certain job. It also feels overwhelming that there are so many options. And I want a job that's somewhat prestigious and pays decently. Ideally, something that matters to me as well. 
I think work is kind of draining for me. I do enjoy working because I like making money, and I want to be more self-sufficient. I like most of my co-workers, and I don't mind the work I do. It's still tiring, though, and I think it contributes to burnout sometimes. As I said, I like my co-workers, and I would like to get closer to some of them, but it's hard to cross over to being actual friends instead of co-workers. Also, since it's a new quarter, scheduling is different, and I don't get to see some of my favorite co-workers from last quarter, so that made me sad.
I think I just feel tired a lot in my everyday life, maybe because I'm trying to do too much. I feel anxious a lot too, often about inconsequential things. I feel lacking in motivation to accomplish my tasks, but I usually get the things done that I need to do. I don't really confide much in other people about this stuff. Normally I just talk about surface-level things. Sometimes I write in my journal when I feel like I have a lot to get off my chest but don't want to say it to other people. I listen to music a lot, which is comforting and motivating for me. Music is important to me.

name: Jabez Domngo
GenItems_narr:
My life is very structured and I like it that way. I wake up everyday around 8-9. I dislike mornings and the last thing I want to do is talk to someone right when I wake up. To avoid this, I only wake up/get out of bed right before I need to go to class/work. I have this down to a tee since I do the same thing every day so I don't have to worry about missing the bus. On days in which I have class/work later in the day, I get out of bed at 9 otherwise I will fine like a bum and it ruins my whole day energy-wise. Although I am almost always low energy. I only use large amounts of energy when I really have to. 

I then take the bus to work/class. My response to class is typically the same in all cases. I don't care to be there. If there is a remote option then I will stay or do whatever I wish and watch the recording later. In general, I dislike being is places that are largely populated as it tires me out to be there. Classes are not an exception to that attitude. People are just a hassle to deal with. They are unpredictable and problematic. They throw a wrench in my plans and it upsets me. I am not totally attentive during class. I get disinterested if the speaker is too slow and if I feel like it is a waste of time being there. Ever since quarantine, that feeling has become more prevalent since I've gotten used to watching lectures on 2x speed. 

I have work on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays. I'm always tired after work. It helps when I have a friend there with me for a majority of the time. On Tuesdays and Thursdays, in addition to class, I go bowling between classes. I really enjoy those times since I feel like I don't get much free time to myself. When I'm bowling I typically become very focused on trying to get better and score as high as I can even if I am playing by myself. 

After I get home from school, I take an hour break watching YouTube or playing mobile games then I do homework which I usually do till 9 or 10. At that point, my brain cannot function so I say 10 is the point at which "productive hours" end. After productive hours, I get ready for bed. This is my favorite part of the day. Every other part of the day is subject to change depending on circumstances but my nightly routine is always the same. It is extremely relaxing for me. That is the time I decompress from the day. I can feel the stress being washed away as I brush my teeth, take a shower, and clean my face. After that I go to bed and fall asleep watching YouTube. Everything loops from there.

name: Julia Huang
GenItems_narr:
I often get anxious at bedtime and take a long time to fall asleep, which makes me very tired when I wake up because I only get 6 hrs of sleep. Anxiety sources include medical school application, work stress, etc. I'm a very anxious person, so these thoughts keep me up at night. When I wake up, I always tell myself that I'm going to take a nap during lunch break after the morning shift, but I never end up doing this because I call my boyfriend or talk to my coworkers or go to Starbucks for coffee.

I work at a pediatrics clinic as a scribe - my mood is often ruined by various factors, most common ones being: long visits due to anxious parents (they will have a list of 20 questions such as "my baby burped once 2 weeks ago. is this normal?" and take an extra 20+ min when we only allocate 15-30 min per patient), complicated patients for example discussing mental health (these take 80 min and puts us very behind schedule), and getting let out late due to a busy schedule (per contract, we're supposed to be let out for lunch by 1:25 PM but it's very awkward to ask the doctor this in the middle of the visit so nobody ever does it).

Bay Area traffic is awful, so I'm always irritated by this. It takes 50 min to get home usually. Having graduated from Davis, I've been living at home, and it's very isolating not seeing friends anymore. I definitely get lonely at night since I don't have anyone to talk to. I don't enjoy going to work because it's minimum wage and they overwork us, but I love talking to my coworkers and getting some human interaction.

I also tell myself I'm going to sleep early every night, but I never end up doing it - I end up scrolling youtube/insta for too long or playing games.

name: E P SHALOOB AHAMMED
GenItems_narr:
Usually my day start with a good happy mood depending on the environmental surroundings and room mates attitude.
Especially the morning 8am sunshine brighten my body and makes me energetic. The breakfast will also give me a good mood for the rest of the day.
After taking a bath to move for my collage i will ge to even more satisfaction.

The first two hours of the class will be ok but after that untill the lunch mood began to change some days i was daydreaming by looking the professors face.
 After the lunch yea some days it feel like to took a good nap sleep but due to class hours its not possible so again starts the boaring hours ... 

At Evening when the last hour bell rang its the moment when we will get an extra energy to go to room chilling with friends outing at late nights having a tea.. yea its all works like a joyful journey.

name: Kathryn Berzas
GenItems_narr:
I’m not really a morning person - I tend to wake up between 9:30 and 11:30 but only with effort. I get between 5 and 8 hours of sleep a night. Most of my day is sedentary - I’m usually employed but not working right now due to a rib injury. My parents are mostly supporting me, and I spend the vast majority of my time alone because of it - I have existing mental health issues that it exacerbates, but I’m not really on great terms with my roommate (previous bad experiences, social anxiety, and deep dislike of change) and the rest of my friends are employed or in school, so it can’t be helped. It does mess with my head though - I have enough self-worth issues without adding “failure to launch” lol. I’m working on getting the injury fixed (to loop back around to the point), which will likely involve a bunch of doctors appointments over the next few weeks.

Most of my day is alternating between writing, drawing, gaming, and taking online skill courses. Usually I’ll watch streams or listen to music in the background (I’m like….99.99% sure I have ADHD, and need 100% of my brain occupied at all times or I will actually combust), but sometimes I’ll be on a phone call with one of my parents or something. Most of my interaction with others comes via text, so it gets pretty lonely. Talking to someone just hits different. I do have a cat though! Her name is Molly, sometimes I take her out on walks around our apartment complex, and I talk to her like she understands me. Sometimes I swear she does lol. I also don’t usually cook - it takes a loooooot of energy for me, so I rely on frozen stuff, take out, and easy one-pot meals with pasta or rice. I feel better physically if I’m eating something I’ve made (it feels healthier if that makes sense?), but I already have issues with eating enough so I’m very much in “all calories are good calories” mode.

My one consistent weekly obligation is therapy! Every Friday afternoon, I have a zoom call with my therapist. Depending on what we talk about, my emotional state tends to vary. Im usually more calm before I go in, then have a few hours of being emotional afterwards while I process whatever we dug up. It doesn’t usually last more than a day or so absent other triggering situations. 

When I am able to be more social, either because my friends are free or because I’m able to branch out through my anxiety, my mood improves. I actually enjoy being around people - like 90% of the ones I’ve run into suck though, hence the social anxiety. The social stuff usually happens on weekends and tends to involve either hanging out at their apartment or going bar hopping through Sacramento.

Sorry if this is disorganized! My thought patterns can get hectic and it’s really hard to edit on mobile.

name: Morgan Cianci
GenItems_narr:
The typical week in my life looks as follows:
Monday, Wednesday, Friday I work part time 9:30am-5:30pm as a leasing agent at an apartment complex. I enjoy my job as every day has different tasks and experiences, but also no huge surprises. 
On Tuesdays and Thursdays I attend full days of classes from around 9am-6pm. I am enrolled in 3 psychology courses and 1 NPB course. (15 units). I like my classes and wish I would participate more but am shy to speak in front of the entire class. Back in community college I felt more able to participate and speak out loud due to smaller class sizes.
On the weekends I spend time with boyfriend who lives about an hour away (somewhat long distance). We stay in contact and support each other with our goals day to day through phone calls and texts throughout the days of the week.
I am an early bird and usually wake up at about 6:30am every day regardless of my schedule. I always drink a cup of coffee in bed and turn on the tv or music. I usually don’t actually start getting ready for the day until 8-8:30am. 
I try my best to workout after school or work at least 3-4 times a week and still end up in bed at around 9pm.
I only stay up late if my friends/boyfriend want to go out to a bar on the weekends.

name: Michael Playford
GenItems_narr:
My daily life is constant during the quarter on a weekly basis. I work as a teacher in the  mornings, Tuesday through Friday, and go to college immediately after in the afternoon. Almost every day, I am stressing about whether or not I can teach effectively to the students under my care. I am always excited to teach, but am afraid that I may be a bad teacher on days, which is never good. After teaching, I have a five hour lab on Monday and Wednesday, which is very exhausting. I do enjoy it, and look forward to it every week, but I leave very tired, and still have to finish my commute back to my hometown outside of Davis. Tuesday and Thursday I have a bio and history class, both of which are very fun and interesting to learn about. My bio class has a fun professor, and the history class has classroom engagement, which is something that I really enjoy. It is hard for me to make friends in college, so classes like this history class help me to talk to others.
Ultimately, I am very stressed as I want to get into medical school, and am looking at the avenues alone. I feel pressure from my family to do well and succeed all the way to top. This makes it very stressful during schools and medical school searching, as I feel that I have so many people that expect me to do well because I am the "smart one". When getting home, I enjoy playing video games to help relax me from the stress. It also helps me to connect with my brother, who is stationed in Japan currently. Aside from this and college classes, I have little interaction with people outside of my immediate family.
Whenever I do get stressed, especially during homework or study sessions, I will resign to my bed and watch Youtube videos. This helps me to see someone who has succeeded or is doing something fun, and tends to cheer me up. I have always found that it makes me very happy to watch and help someone achieve their goals. Usually, I prioritize others over myself, and will help even at the cost of my own grades.
recently, I have been very tired most days after class, but I think that is due to my long lab schedule. It is also tiring and stressful since my car needs to be repaired, but I do not have a lot of excess cash available to do so.

name: Ysobel Alcantara
GenItems_narr:
I tend to be very lazy and stressed when it comes to going out, going to classes, and talking to people. With my classes and the three clubs I'm helping to run, plus some extra clubs/socials on the side, I feel like I'm a lot more drained and occupied than I'm usually comfortable with. I've been trying to better myself for the past couple of years due to issues I had with mental health I had in high school (nothing extreme or something to be worried about, it's just an experience I had back then). Because of that, I've been working on bringing myself to engage more in the world/people around me and have a more optimistic attitude. So even though I tend to complain about how my life is busier than I want it to be and I'm out of my comfort zone a lot, I do think that it's something I want to continue with and generally make me a better person. On Fridays, the tea club I'm vice president of meet up. Therefore, throughout the week, I'll probably be stressing about it, from bringing teas/food, making sure we have a place to meet up, and how many people will show up. But after the club, I end up feeling pretty fulfilled and happy meeting everyone who showed up and talking to them. This is a cycle I tend to go through a lot: worrying about something for what I think is way longer than necessary, only to feel pretty satisfied once the actual thing comes and then passes. 

On a more general topic, I'm a Filipino third-year psychology major. I can't say being Filipino has really affected my daily life in any largely impactful way, but I do feel the slightest bit of pressure every once in awhile. I grew up in a very social and family-oriented environment, and I feel like I am very much neither. Especially in social settings, I feel like there's this expectation to be social and upbeat, since that's the stereotypical personality of someone who's Filipino, so that tends to be on my mind. 

I also tend to ramble and get very lost in tangents. Case above. Don't ask me too many things about my identity as Filipino, because I'll probably just end up saying the same things over and over.
GenItems_Unique_item_2: stressed when it comes to going out
GenItems_Unique_item_6: engage more in the world and people around me
GenItems_Unique_item_7: working on haveing a more optimistic attitude
GenItems_Unique_item_10: feel pretty satisfied once the actual thing comes
GenItems_Unique_item_11: feel the slightest bit of pressure
GenItems_Unique_item_14: expectation to be social and upbeat

name: Gordon Wu
GenItems_narr:
One of the things that I always think about is my bodily appearance. Even though I'm skinny and I go to the gym, I still feel like I'm not muscular or strong enough to reach my goal. When I am around my gym buddy, he looks so much better and he always has the time in his schedule to go to the gym. I think this stems from what I was like as a person when I was younger. I didn't do sports, and I was very scrawny. Going to the gym was a way to reclaim my confidence, which is good and all, but inside I still feel that feeling of resentment of myself and how I considered myself lame all these years.

I'm always thinking about relationships. I always wondered if I would ever get into a relationship. I always think about how people back then got into a relationship, but it just seems so much harder. I would want to be in a relationship, but it always scared me. I'm afraid of the repercussions if something were to happen and we wouldn't be friends anymore. Recently, my housemate is dating another housemate within the same apartment, and it triggered these thoughts about relationships that I don't really know how to navigate.

I have this desire to go to medical school, but the road to reaching it seems very hard. One of the classes I have to take is organic chemistry, and the class stresses me out very much. It's the second quarter of the organic chemistry series, and I am not very confident about it because the content relies on things we learn from the first quarter. It stresses me out because I didn't do that well in the first quarter of organic chemistry, so it is pretty stressful.

I always think about cooking food. Last quarter was very stressful, considering that I had a lot of extracurricular activities to do on top of taking 4 STEM classes. Cooking food is an outlet for me to destress from my responsibilities and I found a lot of joy in it. It's always a good opportunity to cook with my housemates and my friends and just enjoy each others' company.

I don't want to say that I am a people pleaser, but I do try my best to get along with the people that I interact with. I think I am the type to want to make small talk with people even if I meet them for the first time. I think I'm like this because I don't want to be perceived as an antisocial person and that I want others to perceive me as someone who can hold a conversation. I think that is something that I definitely value when I talk to another person.

name: Larisa Castellanos
GenItems_narr:
I am a lazy person, and most of the time does not want to get out of bed. about a year ago I had depression and anxiety, it was hard for me to have the energy I did not want to do anything at all, and I did not have any expectations of myself. I thought that this was not something bad it was normal and will pass, and did not want to get help. after a time I find help and I have been in therapy for about 6 months, and I have been feeling better.

On daily basis, I just started exercising, I have been not feeling well at all, not having energy at all, and I want to do well and my classes, it is hard when I'm alone, or when I am just in my room I feel trapped. I like to be out, go to walk, and talk to someone  who makes me feel better like my boyfriend or my roommate, it feels good to have someone as company

name: stephanie ortega
GenItems_narr:
I am a very motivated person but in college ive been feeling less motivated. I feel like I was burnt out in highschool, I took IB Classes and it took so much of my time and effort that now coming to college I am not as motivated. I also feel like I am barely learning anything. I take so much notes but none of it is stuff im actually learning.

I am a first-generation college student, there is so much pressure on me to be amazing in life. Not even by my parents, but by myself too. I have two younger brothers and I want to be a role model. I want to be successful in life so I could help my parents out. Sometimes I get a wave of anxiety or sadness at night because I have a fear of being a failure.

I honestly started giving up so easy in college. Although I do all my work and stuff. It is very tempting for me to drop classes when I see there's an assignment that will be too hard for me to complete.

In college, the friends I have made come from a very different background than me. Even searching for apartments for next year is a crazy experience because I come from a family that isnt as fortunate money wise. However, my friends are different and theyre parents make way more money than mine. At one point they were looking at apartments way above my budget. I felt stressed. How were my parents going to afford that? I ended up telling them I found a cheaper apartment and I would be living there, with random roommates if they ended up choosing the nicer apartment (if my parents had the money I would). They were nice enough to still choose to live with me though. It was a hard conversation.

name: Helena Sherman
GenItems_narr:
I like to tell myself that I will get up early in the morning, like around 6am or 7am and go to the gym to get my workout in so I don't have to think about it for the rest of the day. The reality is that my alarm goes off at 7am every day and I immediately hit snooze and sleep in until I absolutely have to start work at 9am. I really just struggle with having a consistent routine throughout the day and it's something that I want and I don't know why I can't stick to one. I think I'd feel so much more like a functioning human being if I knew I could wake up at the same time every day and go to bed at the same time and have some consistency on a day to day basis. And I constantly fall into the trap of "I'll be better tomorrow" "I'll go to bed on time tonight and then tomorrow will be perfect" and then it's not perfect, or at least it doesn't go according to how I wanted it to go. 

I am grateful that I have a job that I like doing every day that's not super high stress, but right now I'm in between projects so I don't feel like I'm actually doing that much during the workday outside of doing more learning/development/reading things rather than actual writing work or being in meetings. I also love the flexibility of working from home - I think I'd start losing my mind a bit if I had to go into the office every day - but I also feel like I don't have close relationships with anyone at work that I could see in person. A lot of my coworkers are older and the ones who are my age are not in my area so I don't see them often, and every time I go into the office I just go into a quiet corner by myself because I don't know anyone to sit near and I envy the people who have the assigned desks because they worked at the company prior to remote work and know people that they interact with. It's weird to be in this generation of adults who graduated during COVID and don't have any in-office experience with work, I feel like it's had a lasting effect on my social life.

name: Leslie Fregoso
GenItems_narr:
Typically on Monday’s are my most sluggish feeling days. After a fun exciting weekend, I go back to school and start with my extra curricular activities. My Tuesdays and Thursdays are my longest days of the week. I start it off with going to the gym. Going to the gym, really gives me the boost of energy I need for my morning and the rest of the day. I then proceed to soccer practice. This is one of my favorite times of the day because I get to see all my friends and mess around a bit before practice. Soccer is one of my passions and being able to share that with my teammates that are also my best friends is amazing. After Monday and Tuesday the week repeats its self. 

Overall, I am typically an energetic person, but I do have my off days where I just want to lounge around and be by myself. Having that balance of being energetic and that time off to re-charge is important to me on my day to day.
GenItems_Unique_item_3: tuesdays and thursdays and longest days
GenItems_Unique_item_5: practice and favorite time of day
GenItems_Unique_item_9: mess around and be with friends
GenItems_Unique_item_10: after monday and tuesday and week repeats itself

name: Jeremiah-David Addai
GenItems_narr: I'm usually very energetic, lively and the first to crack a joke and externally I come off as very relaxed. Internally, I feel conflicted because I feel like I'm putting on an act the moment I wake up until the moment everyone is asleep and I'm still up at 3 AM feeling like I'm somewhere I shouldn't be. On a regular basis I wake up, receiving a measly 4 hours of sleep. I then proceed to do one of the 3 following things; consumption of food, homework or socializing. I don't particularly like any of the three activities that take up most of my time, however there is simply nothing else for me to do. I lack drive and passion and I feel like I've been stagnant for so long.
GenItems_Unique_item_6: I put on an act for the outside world

name: Ava Gutierrez
GenItems_narr:
I always wake up tired. I go to sleep between 11-12 and wake up between 7-9. On tuesdays and thursdays i have the busiest schedules. I have classes from 8am -6pm and always make room to hang out with friends in the dorms. My roommate is my best friend and our friends are all the same. these days are pretty frustrating and exhausting. Mondays I don’t have any classes which makes prep for the week much easier. 

Wednesdays and fridays I have one discussion which allows time to go to ARC classes and study. I really enjoy being with the people on my floor but I often find myself exhausted and take several naps throughout the day.
GenItems_Unique_item_6: Enjoy being with the people on my floor

name: Soila Martinez
GenItems_narr:
I am usually a person who thrives on a routine and needs to know what my week will be looking like a week in advance. I work and go to school on a set weekly schedule, usually leaving me with the weekends to enjoy off. I use to be a morning person but last summer I found it very difficult to wake up early in the morning and go to the gym before work (9am shifts). Currently I'm attending the gym 3 times a week, very early in the morning due to school.  I work 4 days out of the week and usually whenever there's a school break I try and work more hours instead of enjoying my break. 
I am a transfer student at Davis, finishing up my last two quarters before I graduate. It's been difficult to make friends on campus due to being a commuter and always working. Therefore, I feel that I am simply just getting by. I am excited to finally be done with my BA and do not think I will be continuing any further education down the road. School has never really been appealing to me but have made it this far because I thought the knowledge would be useful and it seemed like an easy career path. 
Outside of school and work, I enjoy going on hikes, cooking, exploring new restaurants and tending to my aquatic friends.

name: Sanyukta Rohom
GenItems_narr:
Usually, I start my days off with a lot of energy. No matter what has happened or is happening seems to affect me right after I wake up. If I'm in a bad or frustrated mood the night before, going to sleep really helps me just look past that and start the day afresh. Most days I feel good when I'm surrounded by my friends at Davis. I have realized that I'm a social person and I need people around me to feel good. Whenever I'm around some specific people it just relaxes my mind like I'm recharging, but that's only with my few closest friends. 

But there are days when it all starts off bad and the day just goes downhill. I feel like that is usually a pointer to the fact that I'm either running out of my social battery or I'm burnt out. On those days, no matter who I'm around I seem to be quiet and irritable. But it only lasts 1-2 days maximum and after that I feel alive with energy again. So I guess it's my minds way of shutting down, giving me a break, and rebooting the system.

name: ALICE IP
GenItems_narr:
I see myself as a very spontaneous person. I like agreeing to things in the moment and typically do no regret my in the moment agreements (ie agreeing to go out somewhere). But when I agree to do something and have time to think about it, I end up dreading it and regretting agreeing to it in the first place and would rather stay at home.
Most days I have little to no appetite to eat, but following the periods of low appetite which lasts days to weeks, I have days where I crave various foods. During those days, I don't eat because I feel hungrier but because I can't get enough of the flavor of the foods I crave.
I'm not super outgoing, but I can still have a decent conversation with most strangers. If everyone is new and getting to know each other, I do well. But when I'm meeting a group of people who already know each other, I shut down and don't talk and pretend to be engaged by listening. I think I think its embarrassing to ask get to know you questions that everyone else knows the answer to. I would never think its embarrassing if someone else is new to my group, the mindset only applies to me.
I prefer hanging out with one or two people at a time because it feels like my presence matters more if there are fewer people. If I can disappear in a crowd/large group of friends, I wouldn't make an effort to stand out.
I procrastinate a lot. I end up getting my work done eventually though. This is actually an attempt at procrastinating other things I need to get done. I tend to push my work till late at night and sometimes it gets too late. In those cases, I push them off till the next day.
I have moments where I want to grind out my tasks and be productive. I don't know when it happens or what I do to encourage it from happening. I think its usually at night before things are due or if it a scheduled task with someone else like a group project.
I'm not sure what kind of descriptions about me you are looking for, so apologies if I didnt answer the prompt right.

name: Sidney Salmon
GenItems_narr:
My daily habits are usually quite predictable depending on whether it is a work day or not. On my work days (currently Wednesday through Friday), I wake up exactly at 6:00AM. My first thought is almost always to tell myself to get up right away so I don't run the risk of falling back asleep and being late for work. The first ten steps are usually the most difficult since I'm still getting adjusted to standing up after abruptly forcing myself to do so. Because of that, my mood is pretty low since I'd rather be in bed getting a full eight hours of sleep. Once I get up and moving, my mood slowly begins to reach a neutral baseline where I don't feel anything. My mind is too slow to think of anything or feel any type of way about anything. Once I get to work at 7:00AM, it takes me about 30 minutes to fully wake up. Socializing with my coworkers also helps because they are all very positive and supportive. I work at a farm where we do a lot of manual labor, so we have a strong sense of community since we work very hard alongside one another. The day drags on usually until the clock strikes 3:45PM and I can go home.

Once I arrive at home, I feel a bit of relief. I also tend to feel a little bit upset upon my arrival because I know a good portion of my day will be spent in the dark since the sun sets not long after I arrive. Especially on days I have work the next morning, it feels like the rest of the evening is just a transition into the next workday, which is a bleak way of looking at it I suppose. I socialize with my roommates a bit throughout the evening. We usually catch up on our days and tend to gossip about the small dramas going on in our individual lives. It makes me happy to have fun discourse about that kind of stuff (possibly because it makes me feel like part of a community). I also have a cat who always makes my day a little bit brighter.

On non-work days, I have usually been oversleeping a bit. I wake up no later than 10:00AM though, and get my day started with breakfast. If I hadn't already made a to-do list for the day, I'll do that pretty early on as well (which subsequently reminds me to take my adderall). I almost always finish everything by 2:00PM, with the exception of my laundry and my homework. I tend to procrastinate on those two tasks more than any others. I think it's because they are the most time consuming and provide the least amount of instant satisfaction compared to other things I can be doing. 

I feel happier during the week when I have plans for my days off. It gives me something to look forward to. 

After this Friday, I will have a week off from work and be starting a new job on Monday, February 6th. I'm excited for that, but a bit nervous because I will be working full time Monday through Thursday from 6:00AM to 5:00PM. I will wake up before the sun rises, and arrive home just before the sun sets. I am afraid that will negatively impact my mood. I am looking forward to the increased income though, which I will be using to save for college.

name: Gabe Caballero
GenItems_narr:
My daily routine starts at a reasonable time, usually around 8:30 am. I have a lecture Mon. and Wed., but sometimes I don't feel like going to them because the slides are posted and this is just a GE class for me. I think with how much I have on my plate is the reason why I'm not motivated to go to that class. I do have a class on Tues where attendance is mandatory, so I make sure to go to that. 
After my morning class, I'll usually come back home where I feel most comfortable to do work, eat some food, and relax. I'm sure I feel more relaxed at home because this is where I live, I have access to all my things here, and I have a desk set up that I highly prefer over setting up in the library. Comfortability is everything to me when I study and do homework. 
Then after doing homework and getting food, that usually takes me to my now daily afternoon nap that I always take before work. I am a big napper; sometimes I find that I cannot function without a nap, and I am not entirely sure why that is the case, maybe it is because I don't get enough sleep at night, or it has just become so much of a routine that breaking it will send me into "withdrawals" so to speak.
After my nap, I go to work where I work with children with autism. That could also be a reason for my naps, because I deal with kids for my job which can be a big handful. My clients are pretty obedient and not very troublesome for the most part. I am always not excited to go to my Wed client because the session is for 3 hours (my other ones are 1.5-2.5 hours), he lives all the way in Elk Grove, and he is super energetic, talkative, does not always hear or understand me, and does not appear to be progressing much in some of his programs. 
After work, I just go home and go back to doing homework usually. Tues and Thurs I have a lecture that I also do not attend, but may start to because not doing so has really made me more busy with homework. I am honestly getting so exhausted already from my workload this quarter just from my two psych classes. There are just lots of assignments for both classes which means that there are multiple ways to earn (but also potentially lose) points. And I have always been a diligent and studious student that always pushes myself to get work done on time. I think that is why I am exhausting myself in the sense that I need to get everything done by the deadline and I think I have turned it into a philosophy that late work or sloppy homework is a bigger deal than it is. I do work really hard though, and I do have the GPA and consistently good grades to back it up, but it is really draining on me. 
Sometime I hang out at my frat that I'm in which is always a good stress reliever and mood booster. As long as I do not have homework due that night that I need to come back home to do, I always enjoy my time there and don't rush anything. I love hanging out with my big who truly has become like another big brother to me and all the other guys are so accepting and inclusive. I do feel a disconnect sometimes though because it is not very often that I show up (I wish I could've lived in our chapter house), and also because I am gay, so I do not relate to the same things as them, but often I am able to conversate with them about something. It is not hard for me to hang out with them most of the time and joke around with them. I do feel a bit of a pressure to be around more often because I want to connect more with them, but also I think my activity level there could be a contingency when I plan to run for cabinet for next year--another thing on my plate.
I also am a part of a research lab as a research assistant which is also a big commitment (expecting 10 hours per week). It is hard to update my availability this quarter for that since I am busy with my other work and just everything else I have going on. Since I am a part of running studies, though, it is easy to get my hours up since a single visit is half of my required work time for the week. I am excited to finally start that after a quarter of training, but I hope I have sufficient time for it. 
I do also like to go out on weekends. I try my best to grind out homework during the day so that I can go out at night with less on my mind. I made it my goal to have more fun this quarter, so I hope I can stay on top of everything. When I don't stay on top of it, though, that's when it starts to exhaust me and make me feel depressed because I feel trapped and lonely when I feel like I have no choice but to finish all my work. Or I will go out anyway, but often think about the homework I need to finish or regret putting it off until Sunday to finish.

name: Ankit Sinha
GenItems_narr: I am currently pursuing a  computer science degree and have recently started learning to code. But, I am not sure whether I want to be a professional programmer or not. Also from the last few days, I am not able to focus on my studies as much as I want. And, I think this is happening because I am not entirely sure whether the goal that I have selected for me is right or not. There are many carrier paths in front of me that I can take and my confusion to decide which path to take is troubling me.
GenItems_Unique_item_1: There are many carrier path in front of me that I can take
GenItems_Unique_item_2: I am not sure whether I want to be professional programmer or not
GenItems_Unique_item_3: I am not entirely sure the goal I have selected is right or not
GenItems_Unique_item_4: I am not able to focus on my studies
GenItems_Unique_item_5: I am pursuing computer science degree
GenItems_Unique_item_6: I recently started learning to code
GenItems_Unique_item_7: I have little confusion over my carrier option
GenItems_Unique_item_8: I want to explore other carrier paths as well
GenItems_Unique_item_9: But I don't have much free time to do so
GenItems_Unique_item_10: I have to re evaluate my goals
CT_2: Strive to be the best in what I do and in whichever field I am.

name: Kalani Kahandawala Arachchige
GenItems_narr:
I start my day off around 6 am and I do feel a little tired however after brushing my teeth I do feel energized. Throughout the day, I do not feel an influx of emotions rather I feel content. For most days I feel kindness and to be kind and understanding towards myself and others. On Wednesday however, I do feel lazy and exhausted given I have a 3-hour chem lab. 

On teusdays I feel similarly given this is usually the day I complete my PreLab and those prelabs take hours to complete. These two days are when I feel at my lowest however the rest of the week I try to maintain my productivity.

name: Tazlina Dentinger
GenItems_narr:
I tend to wake up fairly energetic, and like to do more work in the morning than the evening. I don't socialize a lot in the mornings, as I tend to be in large lecture classes or in my apartment, where my roommates are late-night people and are usually not awake. I am productive as possible before lunch, though if I'm working for long periods of time my mind often wanders to the podcasts I've been listening to or books I've been reading or other more interesting topics. After lunch I generally get in a few more hours of productivity, but often have trouble concentrating after 4 or 5 pm, either out of habit or because I've already been awake and working for hours. 
On campus, I still spend a lot of time alone during the week because I tend to be more productive that way, and don't mind it. I enjoy and am engaged with most of my lectures, as being in a setting where other people are focused tends to help me focus. The possible exception is my 6pm to 8pm lecture, which is after I would rather not be thinking, and I'm often a little more distracted, though somehow being in a lecture hall still lets me focus to some degree. 
I also do archery in the evenings 2 days a week, and in the mornings on the weekend. The board for archery is fairly close knit, and I often come away from practice feeling physically and socially energized - despite generally being introverted I'm comfortable enough around most of those people that the chance to socialize and goof around is welcome. 
I mentioned I'm fairly introverted - being out of my apartment and active and socializing for longer than I'm used to (say more than 8 or so hours) tends to make me mentally and physically tired. Because of this I often skip social events I'm invited to to take a break, which is a bummer as I would enjoy going, but often I badly need the break. 
Occasionally in the evenings my roommates will be around and we have great, often silly conversations, which are fantastic. I look forward to times when our schedules overlap enough to do that.
GenItems_Unique_item_10: mind wanders to podcasts or books

name: Gillian Penalez
GenItems_narr:
I'm a student who is going through nursing school to become an LVN. Currently, my schedule involves going to clinical on Monday and Tuesday for 12 hours. I'm off on Wednesdays and I have my theory classes on Thursday and Friday for about 6-7 hours. I hate going to clinical for 12 hours. It's really tiring and I have no energy when I get home. It's really annoying getting up early as well. It's a good thing my instructor is pretty great though. She's nice and teaches us well. She even lets us go early sometimes. I'm not close with my peers though. I'm more of a loner and I don't make friends easily so that's why. However, I don't mind. I have a partner that I talk to on a daily basis so I don't get lonely. I enjoy having Wednesdays off. I use it to relax and study a bit for my theory classes the following days. On Thursday, I have my Medical-Surgical class. I'm currently doing well in it. The instructor is good but is a bit tough. I have that class again on Friday along with Pharmacology. I'm not doing well in that class at the moment. The instructor is pretty bad at teaching and isn't communicating with us well so that's hurting my grade. I need to study more to bring up my grade in that class. 

My weekdays are pretty uneventful. My routine mostly consists of playing video games, watching youtube, and listening to music. I also get in a bit of studying. I like playing RPG games. Right now, I'm playing a game called Fear & Hunger 2: Termina. It's a really fun and unique experience. I watch youtube videos of that game as well. I like listening to rock music. My favorite bands include Nirvana, Foo Fighters, etc. I really don't like the food at my house so I constantly get takeways from nearby restaurants. That's pretty much all for my weekends since I don't do much. Sometimes, I run errands here and there as well.

name: Naya Spencer
GenItems_narr:
My name is Naya Spencer and I am a very social individual. I struggle with bad anxiety and take medication to help myself navigate through the day. I am a motivated person with goals and ambitions, however, recently I've been confused about the course of my life and what I can do to help the world. My dad is a white male from upstate New York and my mother is a first generation immigrant from Damascus, Syria. I get my personality from my mom, as she is a very sociable and charismatic person. I love being busy and constantly adding events to my calendar, color coded of course. I would 100% describe myself as being a type A personality and an organization/control freak. 

I usually have a mid-day lull, around 3-5 ish where I feel bored. When I feel like this I usually go the gym or a coffee shop downtown, to kill time before my next class. I get sad when I see animal videos on instagram and think about the effects of climate change. I get scared from horror movies, no matter the horror level--everything scares me with them. I feel happy when I am surrounded by my amazing friends and meditating.

name: Ayush Sinha
GenItems_narr:
I wake up feeling excited about the life, I look up to each day as an opportunity to become a better version of my self. I live each day at a time, trying not to worry about the future much(instant future) but I do have a broad vision about how I want my life to be in a distant future. I like talking with people but only with those who share a common vibe with me else I think I am the most introvert person alive.

I would like to be an entrepreneur at some point in future. I love solving problems and I like to take things as challenge. I am learning programming and Artificial Intelligence.
GenItems_Unique_item_2: each day opportunity to become better

name: Sayaka Shoy
GenItems_narr: I feel that I am much more productive in in the hours before afternoon. I try to wake up early most days even if I don’t have to because I feel that I can get more done. I notice that after lunch toward the afternoon I get extremely tired and I think this is partly because of eating and feeling sluggish but also because I tend to go to sleep late and wake up early. I also really like coffee and I think I hit a caffeine crash later. I also noticed that I can’t study well in my dorm room because I get easily distracted by other things I would rather do than my homework. I like to go to the lounge, cafes, and libraries to get work done because I feel that I can be more productive. I also can’t study with talkative people because I find that we rather end up talking instead of being productive together. I noticed that when I am outside of the dorm I also have less of an “appetite” and I think that’s because I don’t see any food around me so i just forget about it. I also feel that I don’t deal well with interruptions. I can go a long time doing important things but as soon as I get interrupted I have a lot of trouble getting back in to the zone. I feel that my mood everyday is pretty happy and energetic but I find that I sometimes shut down in the middle of the day randomly and don’t want to be social at all. I am not exactly sure of the cause and why it tends to be so random.

name: Cristal Garcia
GenItems_narr:
I'm usually energetic but I do need to take naps every other day. I have been taking naps since middle school so taking them now isn't anything unusual for me. Most of the day, I am usually talking to my suite mates or doing homework. Somedays I do feel more anxious than others. I try my best to hide these feelings to avoid concerning anyone. Feeling anxious is usually caused my some internal thoughts or is triggered by something that I saw. 
 I'm not a morning person so attending my classes on Tuesday and Thursday can be hard since I don't want to wake up. There are some peers who trigger my first gen identity more than others but it's usually because they have no understanding to some of the struggles that first gen may encounter and some make it seem irrelevant.

name: taylor balantac
GenItems_narr: Usually I wake up early around the same time everyday. Sometimes I feel really tired but I always get out of bed and get ready then go eat breakfest or go to the gym. I feel good when I get up early and go these things it makes me feel like I started the day off productive. Most days I feel energetic but sometimes I recognize myself to be slow and unmotivated to socialize. Sometimes i think it is because I don't get every ounce of attention but it is okay because I tend to lose my energy after a while. When I am around my friends I feel included and happy. I get dinner with my coworkers and it gives me the opportunity to talk and interact after a long day of being in class.

name: Angela Ung
GenItems_narr:
I see myself as someone that doesn’t have a purpose or anything going in my life. I spend most of my time staying in my dorm and having zero interactions with other human beings. I feel like my mood is usually tired and down because I spend most of my time alone in my room. My daily routine is very repetitive and I don’t know if there’s anything that would change that routine. Everyday I struggle to wake up because I didn’t get a good enough sleep that night since I stay up very late, usually around 2 to 3 am. I always tell myself that I need to sleep but I find it very hard to fall and stay asleep. After I wake up, I continue the same routine of going to class, listening to the lectures and then eat lunch, and after that I just stay in my room until I feel hungry enough to go out and eat dinner. 

When I finish my classes for the day I always feel very tired, but I just go on my phone watching Tik Toks or YouTube. I think I feel tired everyday because I always do the same thing. I don’t talk to anyone because I am anti-social and I feel like this affects how my mood is at the end of the day. I want to go out and become more outgoing but I feel stuck and scared to go out of my comfort zone.

name: Tadas Sereiva
GenItems_narr: Every day is the same for me. On weekdays, I wake up between 6:30am and 7am. I usually feel tired because I average 6.5 hours of sleep and my sleep becomes very irregular after 2am. I then go for a run usually between 7-8 miles. I really enjoy these morning runs especially if I can see the sunrise. After my run, I feel excellent and energized. I then bike to work, which is in a molecular biology lab on cam.

name: Annie Xu
GenItems_narr: I feel energetic in the morning, but often feel pretty tired after having classes.

name: Amanda Cable
GenItems_narr:
My identity is largely shaped by my current circumstances- I am a stay-at-home mom and I work part-time, primarily remotely. It is a very lonely existence, despite being constantly “on” and attentive to the needs of others. I wake up and I generally feel very neutral - not happy or unhappy. As I progress throughout the day, my mood and my personality are shaped largely by the moods of my children. They are three (twins), so they are often unpredictable - I do my best to remain calm and compassionate when faced with the many mood swings of toddlers, there are days I am better at it than others.

I think I am often happy, I feel happy, but am prone to daydreaming a great deal and find myself lost in my own thoughts. Primarily as a means of escaping some of the more mundane aspects of my life.

When I am with my peers or at work, I am more prone to be upbeat and genuinely feel that way because I miss those sincere interactions with others my own age. I have a play date with one of my old friends today and I am in a very good mood as I am looking forward to seeing her and hearing about her life later today. These are the things that I enjoy the most, as they allow me to spend time with my children but also allow me to really exist as someone other than a mom.

name: Isabella Huang
GenItems_narr: Since coming to college I have felt somewhat happier and independent. I act according to my own schedule and I do as I please. Because of this, I usually feel pretty happy each day. Every Tuesday and Thursday I wake up at 5:30am to go to the gym, and although it is tiring to wake up that early, it makes me feel very productive. I am able to start my day early on and it feels good stretching out my body. Recently, my schedule has been very busy with work, school, volunteering, and clubs. However, I enjoy how packed my schedule is sometimes because I have a list of things I need to do. On Tuesday, I have a chemistry lab and it makes me feel stressed because I am worried about doing the lab right and if I will finish in time. Lately, I have been craving spam musubi or gushers. I also been trying to spend as much time as I can out of my dorm. I think this is because my dorm has a lot of distractions and my roommate is usually there too. I don't really like it when people are near me when I am trying to do it because I can't focus as much. because of this, I have been going to the library a lot to finish my work. However, the library is a far work so it is pretty tiring going there everyday.

name: Serry Le
GenItems_narr:
Almost every day I go to school, I feel very eager, especially when I go to the gym to play badminton with my friends after finishing all my classes. But when I get home after that, my mood becomes a little down, and usually don't want to do anything else. If the days I go home without playing badminton, I feel kind of restless as if my day is missing something. Even if I get home and still have plenty of time, it's still difficult for me to get started doing homework immediately. 
On the day I don't have to go to school, I don't feel so motivated to work on my assignments. It may be because I think I have the whole day to do it so I keep procrastinating. I often feel irritated for wasting the time but at the same time, I can't focus on studying.
GenItems_Unique_item_3: my mood becomes a little down
GenItems_Unique_item_6: difficult to get started doing homework
GenItems_Unique_item_7: don't have to go to school

name: Aiying Gealey
GenItems_narr:
I am the youngest in my family, with three older brothers and one older sibling. I am also a transracial Asian adoptee with a bilateral cleft lip. On a daily basis, as an Asian-American full-time student, I’m honestly on autopilot for most of the week until the weekend. I guess you could say that it’s a sort of coping mechanism for me because sometimes the stress/fear of not doing well, missing a deadline, failing all of my classes, and the financial burden of attending UC Davis is too overwhelming and my mind looks for some kind of escape. I also have a hard time focusing on my professors for my lectures, like there’s so many thoughts/daydreams that distract me. If I had to put my actions into thoughts I’d say that my thoughts are to wake up, brush my teeth, get ready for classes, motivate(low key force) myself to eat, go to class, listen during lectures/participate during discussions, eat dinner, brush my teeth/wash my face, get ready for bed, and go to sleep. Then my thoughts become more sporadic and spontaneous during the weekends. 

As a young Asian-American woman, I have come to grow wary of my surroundings and slightly fearful of white people (especially men). These feelings have manifested since I started high school, when I started to realize I was being exposed to gender and racial stereotypes/hate crimes from my peers and strangers. Two of the most prevalent events happened in Ireland and Vancouver, where I was spat on by white teenage boys for being Asian, and verbally harassed with my sibling by a homeless man- also for being Asian- in Vancouver. I used to feel great anxiety back in high school just for being Asian and I had no one else to really talk to because the student/general population was mainly white or Latinx. My anxiety has gotten slightly better since coming to Davis as there’s a larger Asian-American & Pacific Islander population. 

In terms of beliefs, I’d say that it mainly centers around freedom and rights for women, women of color, people of color, and people in the LGBTQA+ community. I have these beliefs because I identify with all of these and I have watched and lived through the many problems and horrible stereotypes that have been tied to these identities. In the recent years, I have started to speak out more about women’s rights to their own bodies. I find it despicable that there’s people who lack uteruses that are trying to govern my body and it’s functions, and am pretty much being told that my only purpose is to become an incubator. Every time I hear someone or find out that someone in my social circle expresses these views, I feel so disgusted and frustrated. 

In terms of desires, I can only focus on the present and close future at the moment. I’d like to earn my B.S. without too much stress/trouble, I’d like to be able to lift some of the financial burden of college off of my parents shoulders, I’d like to eventually have a significant other, and I would enjoy having a stable, well-paying career sometime in the next decade.
GenItems_Unique_item_5: Bilateral Cleft Lip and Palate kid

name: Annie Xu
GenItems_narr:
I am an energetic person usually, but I feel pretty tired after having four classes in the morning.

I try my best to do well on academics, and I have confidence I can achieve the goal.

name: Summer Chen
GenItems_narr: I usually feel tired during the day since I don't get enough sleep to spend time playing mobile games and watching dramas with friends online after finishing homework during the nighttime. My dog is living with me, and I walk her every morning and evening. It makes me feel relaxed and content while walking her, just like taking a break. I enjoy cooking even though I just learned how to cook by myself after attending college. My grandma did not allow me to cook when I was young because she thought that was dangerous, so later when I lived with my mom, she got annoyed by me when I wanted to help her in the kitchen because I could do nothing but cause trouble. But I have been interested in it, so I was really excited when I finally got to cook for myself. Since I am not living on campus, I can't make many friends at school as easier as those who live in the dorm. Especially because I am a transfer student, which makes that even harder. But of course, that is only my thoughts, other students may have different experiences than me. I tend to be more introverted these days although I am very energetic in front of my friends. I like making friends with people I like at the first sight. I really believe in my intuition. If I don't like someone, I won't fake myself, but I will always be respectful. I always go shopping or buy groceries alone, and sometimes text my friends to come with me. I won't feel lonely when I am alone, but I will feel very pleased if my friends come with me. Recently, I only feel distressed and scared when exams are coming because it is easy for me to get distracted when I am at my work. I am also careless yet afraid of making mistakes.

name: Deyana Velazquez
GenItems_narr:
In my daily life, studying around other students makes me feel pressured to study. Possibly because seeing others try their best makes me also want to try my best. But sometimes I can’t stand this pressure so I try to find a quiet place, and frequently fail to do so- which is why I often study at home. I take the bus to school and back home, so when I feel tired I can’t really go rest at a dorm or in a car. I feel especially tired in days where I have long periods of wait time between classes- this often makes me want to skip my classes and watch the lecture video when I get home. However, doing that makes me fall behind- especially when I have a lab section where I must know what is going on in class. It’s especially difficult to rewatch lecture videos since I feel like I am not as involved, and don’t have other students around me pressuring me to pay attention or take notes. 

Sometimes when I start studying I easily get distracted. Or if I ever feel pressured and faced with anxiety-when I don’t understand something- I go on my phone and start reading mangas for comfort. They usually take my mind off of things- off of reality- as I read the stories of characters who are able to impress those around them. It’s very comforting, and it gets me excited to see how they face their problems and end with a happy ending. I also often times play music as I study to keep me entertained and not faced with silence. This type of music is usually jazz, phonk, or other random genre.

name: Leana Matibag
GenItems_narr:
I'm usually energetic in the mornings, but when the afternoon hits I lose my social battery or energy. Honestly, I have been feeling this way since the COVID-19 pandemic hit. I feel as if I do not know how to socialize anymore. I get nervous when interacting with new people and have found myself being quiet around them, only talking to them when they talk to me first. 

Also, I have noticed that I have been unmotivated or probably lazy. I have no determination to do things and tend to stay in bed when I have no class. Why do I feel this? Frankly, I always ask myself this too. I sometimes think that I am just lazy, but I also feel that I might be burnt out or depressed?
GenItems_Unique_item_2: lose my social battery or energy

name: Sofia Simon
GenItems_narr: I go to the gym with my friend every Monday, Wednesday, Friday, and sometimes on Sat/Sunday. This makes me very happy because I rarely get to spend time with her outside of this time. I am excited when we go, because this is when we have time to chat and catch up about what has been going on within our lives. Although I truly enjoy this, I also get a bit tired because we wake up around 4:30 am to head to the gym at 5 on these days (except weekends are flexible). This can make me tired because in order to get the proper amount of sleep I need to go to bed around 8pm, but, I usually don't go to bed until at least 10 sometimes 11 pm. Outside of this, my day usually consists of waking up just before my classes (maybe 20 mins before) and quickly getting ready and packing my food from the day before and my electronics so that I'm all prepared for a long day of classes. This can be a bit nerve-wracking because I have to do everything so quickly. I know that this could be solved by waking up earlier, but I value my sleeping time too much. My classes are each 3 hours long, so I am quite tired after my first class, and go to eat a bit of lunch with my friends, which makes me happy. After lunch, we go to our next classes, and, after that class ends, I am truly exhausted from all the work I've done for the day. I end up biking home quickly so that I can take a nap and be refreshed, so that I can then do my homework. After this, I pack my lunch, which is the time I take to watch youtube/tv, and get everything ready to do the same thing over again the next day. I am quite content with my routine, but sometimes I get a bit burnt out.

name: Aven Miller
GenItems_narr: My schedule is very busy right now. I am working part-time at a senior living facility as a server, which can be nice but also extremely stressful. It’s nice when we have enough staff and it isn’t too busy so I can bond with the residents, but that isn’t very often at this point. We are usually understaffed and the residents get very cranky very easily, so it can be an extremely stressful environment. I work there on Mondays, Wednesday, and sometimes Saturdays. I also work as a data entry intern for the MARBLES study for about 5 hours a week on Wednesdays and Thursdays. I’m really excited to be helping out at a research study like this especially considering that Autism affects myself and many family members, so it makes me feel like I’m helping in an impactful way. However, it is a very boring and monotonous job, but it gives me the chance to explore new music artists while I’m entering in the data. I am also the Vice President for a hiking and camping club, which is my main social outlet. I like all of my fellow officers, who I meet with once a week onTuesdays, and I love seeing all of the members when we have socials or go hiking on the Weekends. I will probably be President next year, which is a little stressful because I will have to speak to very large crowds more frequently than I do now, but am not too worried. I am taking interesting classes this quarter, including Physics, Psychology 100Y, Philosophy of Mind Brains and Comp, and Ballet. Physics is very difficult for me, and I really want an A for it this quarter so I am dedicating most of my spare time to studying for it. I try to make healthy meals, but usually have the most stability in my breakfasts, which are either avocado toast with an egg or yogurt with fruit.

name: James Jauregui
GenItems_narr: First thing I do when I wake up at around 5:30-6:00, make some coffee to enjoy in the early morning which is very tasty and gives me energy. I then eat some breakfast which is usually cereal or scrambled eggs with toast. After that I usually rest and check emails etc…. till about 10 am. Around 10 am I go to exercise for about 1-2 hours varies by day and muscle group I work on. After exercising, it’s around 12 o clock, super exhausted around that time and to fix that I would get something to eat usually subway is what I usually get. I usually don’t do much after exercising because most of the time I am so exhausted… but if I’m not tired and have a bit of energy I would go on a bike ride.
GenItems_Unique_item_1: I am usually tired after lunch
GenItems_Unique_item_3: I am energetic after drinking coffee
GenItems_Unique_item_4: exercising helps me with my health
GenItems_Unique_item_5: I do not eat breakfast alot

name: Ella Swadley
GenItems_narr:
I typically wake up every morning in great mood ready to take on the day. However, my mood can quickly change and be influenced by the people I interact with first in the morning. Usually it will be my roommates. If they appear stressed or in a bad mood, that tends to easily rub off on me. As the day goes on, I usually have a lot of energy and excitement throughout the morning to early afternoon. But often times, once it hits around 4, I feel pretty exhausted and not as stimulated or motivated. I tend to take a little break at this time and just do something to recharge, whether it is relaxing, going on a walk, or chatting with my roommates. 

A couple important things about myself to share is that I typically enjoy spending a portion of my day alone, sitting with my own thoughts and processing interactions or experiences that have happened in my day or that have been influencing my life as of recent. I also value my friendships and being emotionally available for my friends. Sometimes this takes a toll on my own mental health, as I tend to take on a lot of other peoples problems, while also managing my own problems. This can get to be overwhelming at times. I am a big people pleaser as well, which ties into that. Another thing about me is that I have recently been trying to find things I am passionate about, as I am in the middle of trying to find a new major (one that excites me). I have been feeling as though I don't have many strong passions, and I want to work on that.

name: Ashley Gleason
GenItems_narr:
I am normally a very happy and confident person, but lately, I've been feeling much more unsure and downcast.  I think this is because I've been having some issues with my roommate.  We used to be very good friends in high school, but our relationship quickly degraded once we got to college.

Most days, I feel hopeful about the things I have going on throughout the day, but on Thursdays and Fridays, I have lab courses that make me feel a sense of dread.  My Thursday lab is for biology which is a subject that I enjoy, but my lab partner is so good at the material that it can become stressful for me when I don't understand things as quickly as she does.  My Friday lab is for organic chemistry which is a subject that I really dislike because I find it especially difficult and time-consuming, so the lab is definitely not something I look forward to going to.
GenItems_Unique_item_5: I feel hopeful about the day
GenItems_Unique_item_6: I feel a sense of dread
GenItems_Unique_item_7: I am feeling stressed about school
GenItems_Unique_item_8: I am anxious about attending my lab classes
GenItems_Unique_item_9: I feel like my classes are difficult and time consuming

name: Janet Azar
GenItems_narr:
I am normally looking to seek social interactions throughout my school day but at the same time I get drained from them quickly. I see myself as more of a surface level interaction person. While I am consumed with school work I find myself always craving social interaction but I often perform best independently. The aspect I like about talking to my peers is that it gives me the sense of being a college student. Many times I regret not immersing myself into many organizations or activities due to my school work load so I try to fill that void by making connections with classmates. 

I also see myself as very abrupt. I don't always think thoroughly before acting on something or saying something. I noticed that others enjoy that about me so many times I don't try to hold back. At the same time, it makes me feel out of place and I normally try to stick to being around people that I feel most comfortable talking to.
GenItems_Unique_item_10: sense of being a college student

name: Leti Fernandez-Acosta
GenItems_narr:
On Mondays Im usually very happy and busy doing what I didn't finish over the weekend- such as homework, laundry, or my dishes- because I don't have any classes on Monday. This extra day allows me to catch up on anything late before my 9AM the following day. More washing and drying machines are available so it's easier to do laundry without any interruptions. I always get breakfast lunch and dinner with my friends and suitemates so that is something I often look forward to since I had been alone all day. 

On Tuesdays and Thursdays, I am usually super slow because I have a class at 9AM-10:20AM. I have to get up super early for this class because I need to get ready and then go eat breakfast before driving to class. Parking is also a drag since everyone parks in the same space. I'm usually very drained. Sometimes I get to nap between my classes because I still have a class to get to at 4:40 PM later on those days. I really dread these days because both times I go to class it is super cold- and I'm from LA so these are conditions I'm not yet accustomed to yet. I don't really talk to anyone from my classes either, so I just feel awkward sometimes walking into my classes.
GenItems_Unique_item_7: not looking forward to Tues or Thurs

name: Marisabel Munoz Chavez
GenItems_narr: I usually wake up feeling unmotivated. Hard to get out of bed. I usually feel ready for the day at 12pm. But by 5 pm I need to nap. Going to school Monday through Thursday keeps me busy and happy. When I don't have plans I usually feel down and like I'm wasting time. Going to work at 1:15 ruins my Wednesdays.

name: Zirui Zeng
GenItems_narr:
At the beginning of the semester, there were mat22A classes at 9am on Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays. But last week, this class was dropped because my waitlist didn't make it. So, my morning class is only Ant 002 on Tuesday and Thursday. This past Friday, I got up at 10am to make breakfast for me and my girlfriend. She ate and then went to school, and I had plenty of time to do my homework at home. With enough rest time while I was out in the afternoon, I had plenty of energy. I love the sunny weather, which is one of the things I love about California. Except for those two weeks of torrential rain at the beginning of the school year, every day my norm is to be bathed in sunshine. I get very low when it's rainy, and I get in a good mood when it's sunny. Whenever I encountered any difficulties in my study, going out to blow the wind and sunshine was my way of dispersing my mind.
I'm an international student from China and I'm sharing a room with four Chinese people. Usually we play games, play cards and talk together. We are all good friends and we are planning to go to Hawaii together during spring break. Sometimes they litter and don't wash the dishes, and I help them out most of the time. It's only when there's a good time that I mention it to them. I am a relatively friendly person and rarely lose my temper with others. I also have a very good relationship with my girlfriend. I usually cook and take care of her at home, and she is a very gentle and beautiful girl. My life in America is very exciting!

name: Jeffrey Johnson
GenItems_narr:
