I tend to be an anxious person and easily get emotional about things. This can be physically noticeable to people, and it does affect my social interactions negatively. When it comes to work, I believe in putting in hard effort, which is reflected in my diligent handling of tasks and responsibilities. Some people have told me that I work too hard, even harder than the people who owns the business I work for and some had even gone to say that i'm trying too hard to impress , but I don't see it as trying to impress anyone. It just feels natural to me.

I identify as a Christian, but religion is not a central part of my life. I believe that the most important guiding principle for all humans should be the Golden Rule, "treat others as you would like to be treated". If more people followed this principle, I think the world would be a much better place.

As previously mentioned, I am a shy and reserved person and often become very tense in social situations. This leads me to limit my social interactions, which has resulted in me having few friends and being single. I am working on changing this behavior, as it has had negative consequences for my personal life.


My biggest desire is for personal and professional growth and development. This includes me setting and achieving career goals, exploring new opportunities, and building relationships and networks. I'm looking to establish a sense of independence and find a sense of purpose and fulfillment in my personal and professional life. I acknowledge that I have been lagging in many aspects, particularly socially, however, I am confident that with greater commitment, I will be able to achieve success.

name: Tiffany Hong
GenItems_narr:
This quarter I am taking a lot less units than I usually am, and it makes me feel like I am not doing a lot when I actually know that I am. On top of my classes, I am in two research labs and I also work part time at a paid job on campus. I sometimes question if I am doing too much and sometimes other people question me. But I keep in mind daily that because my goal is to graduate early, I need to do these things in order to obtain the work experience. Because I am taking less units, I am happy that I get to spend more time taking care of body. I have tried to go the gym 5 times a week since the new year has begun. I am also trying to eat a lot healthier since I have more time to cook meals instead of eating out. 

On a weekly basis I mainly have a set schedule. I am happy that this quarter I can allow my body to sleep in till whatever time it wants to. Last quarter it was really stressful trying to wake up at 6 or 7 am and trying to catch the 8 am bus because the 8:30 am bus would always be late and I had a class at 9 am every day. On the days I have classes, I usually use the bus to get to school. The bus is always busy, sometimes very tight and stuffy. On the days I have work, I usually walk because it takes me 5 minutes to get there. I am glad that I get to live close to my paid job because I know it's not a possibility for everyone. 

In my free time, I try my best to spend time with my partner. My partner makes me really happy, supports me, and I am grateful that we have been together for a good amount of time. I look forward to the days that we can spend time together, especially to go to the farmer's market. When I am home, I try my best to give my family a call. I wish my roommates and I were as close as we used to be. I am really busy so I am not home as much. Two of my roommates do things I don't necessarily approve of because they seem to be failing more classes after they began to do certain things. I feel like it is a correlation and not a causation type of situation. I don't want to judge them or confront them about these issues, but I worry about them and their future because I want them to succeed. My roommates also frustrate me because sometimes they do not their chores on the days they promised to do them and sometimes they do not keep their promises and sometimes they take my things or come into my room without asking, which makes me sad and frustrated.
GenItems_Unique_item_1: less units not doing a lot
GenItems_Unique_item_3: happy take care of body gym

name: Kami Elliot
GenItems_narr:
I think of myself as a positive person. I believe in always trying to develop yourself. Living with integrity is super important to me. I am trying to live with gratitude for all things. I am trying to slow down and truly experience the events in my life. 

I do not like my job and am trying to reframe my experience with it to not be something negative in my life. I am enrolled at Sac State, attempting to obtain a BA while also working full-time. A degree will most likely not change my career outlook, but I still think it is good to push through the challenge and help me grow.

I have been looking to explore my emotions more deeply. I have a long trauma history and have been numb to my feelings for a long time, but I am finally in a safe space to work on myself in that way. 

I have an 18-year-old son who lives with me, and I am working on my relationship with him. Although we are close, we are not open with each other and keep conversations very shallow. He has trouble trusting adults, which is due to the past relationships I have had.

 My goal in life is to be happy, healthy and to form and maintain meaningful relationships with the people I love. Relationships are very taxing for me. I find it takes tremendous energy to keep engaged with them, so it has been difficult for me to do so consistently. Overall, I see good things in my future and believe I will accomplish the goals I have set out for myself.
GenItems_Unique_item_1: I am trying to reframe my experience with my job
GenItems_Unique_item_2: Living with integrity is super important to me
GenItems_Unique_item_3: I am trying to live with gratitude for all things
GenItems_Unique_item_4: I have been looking to explore my emotions more deeply
GenItems_Unique_item_5: I want to form and maintain meaningful relationships with the people I love
GenItems_Unique_item_6: Overall I see good things in my future
GenItems_Unique_item_7: it takes tremendous energy to keep engaged with relationships
GenItems_Unique_item_8: I believe I will accomplish the goals I have set out for myself
GenItems_Unique_item_9: I think of myself as a positive person
GenItems_Unique_item_10: It is good to push through the challenges which help me grow

name: Annelise Gregory
GenItems_narr:
Most days I'm energetic and happy, however, I can be sluggish and tired if I stay up studying too late. I love being at this school and I'm very motivated to do well and attend classes. However, like most students, there are times where I really have to push myself to study, do work, or attend class. I love being around my friends but I enjoy time alone, especially when trying to complete work or study. I would describe myself as talkative when the vibe of the people around me are welcoming and similar to my own. Otherwise, I can come off as shy or rude due to my lack of talking.
    I have a lot of beliefs and motives, many of which fluctuate as I think about them more. A lot of my choices revolves around my desire to succeed. I also have been striving to respect myself more and maintain a peaceful mind, which has also influenced my actions. Due to my beliefs, I tend to keep a small group of friends and even smaller group of people I trust. 
     I often work out as a form of stress relief and to maintain a healthy lifestyle. I also love being in nature and outdoors to clear my mind.

name: Emma Guerrero
GenItems_narr:
My day usually starts around 10am, this is the latest I can wake up without feeling like I have lost any chance of being productive in the day. If i wake up later I feel discouraged and feel like i've lost the day. I need to wake up this early as my morning routine is about 3 hours long. I have severe TMJ so I have to do about 20-30 minutes of physical therapy for my jaw 2-3x a day. I like to split it up and do it in the morning and at night. I've gotten used to it so it feels as necessary as brushing my teeth (even though if I'm out late or wake up late I feel reluctant to do it). For context, my TMJ is so severe that I usually limit how much time I spend with my friends because laughing and smiling for too long makes it hurt and I can only eat foods on the soft side. This has been an ongoing issue for about a year. I also have a torn hip labrum which has caused knee joint issues. This chronic pain makes it hard to sit or walk for too long. I also do 1/3 of my PT in the morning and 2/3 at night (combined about 2 hours long) daily. I've gotten to a point where I try not to think about the debilitating nature of my chronic pain but some days the limitations feel overwhelming. I tend to have less energy doing PT at night because I just want to rest after I've gone to school in the day. I go to school and have mostly online classes to be more flexible with my physical limitations. I try now to at least walk 1000 steps a day.

I notice on days that I don't spend time with my friends, I feel more lonely than not. This could be because I don't hang out much with my roommates and am physically limited on what I can do. I find that on days that I am not busy with school work or professional work, I feel in a more depressed state. This could be because I am left to my own devices. Sometimes I notice people who are jogging or exercising in public, I feel jealous because I wish I could walk normally without pain. If i find myself in a negative mood, I try to listen to music either to calm myself down when stressed or give myself upbeat energy when sad. I also tend to create art whether I am bored, feel creative, or are overwhelmed. I find art as a good outlet when I am sad or overwhelmed. I make an active effort to talk to at least two people a day outside of my house as I know my mood is low when I am left to myself and have not talked to people. After my health issues arose, I realized the impact of having meaningful connections with friends and peers. Around 7pm I usually feel fatigued after my classes and feel like taking a nap. However, I try not to take a nap so I can go to bed at a decent hour (around 12am)
GenItems_Unique_item_6: wake up before or at ten am
GenItems_Unique_item_10: talk to at least two people
GenItems_Unique_item_14: less energy to do PT at night

name: Harnoor Manjal
GenItems_narr: I really enjoy sleeping in, but it makes me more tired. However, if I don't sleep in I can still be tired regardless. I fit in pretty easily and love to socialize. My social battery can get drained and I would then prefer to stay in and read a book or watch tv. I enjoy my week, but despise Tuesday's and Thursday's because I have 3 classes which I'm not a fan of. Two of the three classes are fine, but my online class just drains me because of how long it is. I used to think I was going to be lonely for awhile, but my luck recently has been amazing and now I have amazing friends and people I surround myself with. It makes me enjoy my time here way way way more compared to my first year. It is surreal to me at times. It is really hard for me to work after I take a shower. I always feel like taking a shower will refresh me and make me motivated, but it just makes me want to enjoy my time in bed and just relax.

name: Alec Liang
GenItems_narr:
I am often most energetic during the late afternoons or evenings. I often feel very tired when waking up, but have no trouble staying up to do more work. I personally find going out and interacting with too many people exhausting. This may partly contribute to how I don't feel excited during the mornings since most of my classes tend to be during that time. 

I also feel excited to talk to my friends and learn about new topics. In particular, last quarter I had a lot of enjoyment learning about Greek Mythology. This current quarter, I'm learning about the history of Dinosaurs, which is also very interesting. I think this partly contributes to how I feel excited during my late afternoons and evenings.
GenItems_Unique_item_1: energetic during the late afternoons or evenings

name: Celeste Guerrero
GenItems_narr:
I usually wake up two hours before I have to do something, I have insomnia so it's hard to stick to a routine. I wake up feeling groggy, I feed my cat and say hi to my best friend who I live with. When I'm getting ready I listen to music because otherwise I'll fall back asleep and it helps me think about something else than whatever weird dream I had. I'm too nauseous to eat so I don't until I get to campus, I think I might be avoiding eating a little as well. I'm sad a lot so sometimes I forget to eat. 
Most days I'm excited to go to class except for when I have to wake up at 8am to go on campus for one class. It is hard for me to pay attention in classes that happen before noon, possibly because of the insomnia. There are some discussions in class where I feel left out, because I'm either a first generation student or an immigrant. This however, gives me a view on the content of the class that people may not think about that I think is important in order to make the class accessible for everyone. 
For this quarter, my friend accompanies me to a class she enjoys and it makes the class feel less like a class and more like a YouTube video we are watching together, the discussions make me feel way more interested in the class than if she weren't there. The same applies for the class she's actually in, I tend to pay more attention to class if someone is there to catch things I didn't or when we're at home talking about the class contents it helps that we can talk it out. For the other class my other friend is in it, they like the class more than I do so it's nice to have someone who knows what we're doing when I get bored in class. 
After I get home I usually eat some food while watching a video, then I go to my room and work on my readings. It's easier in the afternoon to do work since I have energy and I'm not groggy, as well as the nausea leaving some time after I leave class. 
During the weekends I go to work in the afternoon, as my job consists of doing whatever it is I have assigned for that day and then leaving, it doesn't take me more than a couple of hours. I don't eat before leaving, because of the nausea so when I get home I eat and then I do chores.

name: Emily McAtee
GenItems_narr:
I usually wake up tired but get energetic after I workout. Getting myself up quickly helps me stay focused for the day. Lately I have felt overwhelmed with the amount of work I have to do. I am excited to represent UCD Law at the National Negotiation competition but I feel unhappy with how much time it takes up. I have been extremely tired between coursework, extracurricular tasks and maintaining a social life. When I am around my friends and peers I am more productive and happy even though they can act as a distractor. 

Usually money is a concern of mine but I have started babysitting so I have felt relief to have some source of money. Most days I am pretty content with my life and tasks but this week I have a lot of practice to do for my upcoming competition and I am dreading the week.

name: Kalani Kahandawala
GenItems_narr: When I wake I typically feel a little lazy, however I do feel motivated. I go shower first thing in the morning so I can feel clean and fresh to start my day. Throughout the day I feel motivated, however when the sun starts to set I start to feel tired and demotivated. Sometimes if I am tired enough I will take a nap at around 4 pm and wake up in time for class at 5. I do get hungry throughout the day and during those times I go to the dining hall and feed my hungers, if I am in a hurry and hungry I grab something from Peet's coffee and do my work. I usually go to sleep around 10 so I can get around 7 hours of sleep so I can be energized for the next day.

name: Phoebe Wong
GenItems_narr:
My usual Days: There is always something new that I am learning or something that I find out that I am somehow involved in. I always hear rumors or news that is pretty relevant to my life. My life is pretty eventful.

About Me: I am currently a Resident Hall Community Advisor, meaning that I have many night shifts and I interact with many freshmen on the daily basis. I live with the freshman and I am older than most of my residents. I am also starting an internship in the month of February. In total, I will be working 40 hours a week ( 20 Hours as a Community Advisor and 20 Hours for the internship) and have a full course load of 16 units. I feel the most stressed in my Community Advisor jobs, especially on weekend rounding because many residents break policies, try to argue with you, and you have to write a lot of reports.

My Daily Life:
Sunday and Saturday: I start of my days waking up later in the day (10-11 AM). I wake up late some days because I have shifts that end at 2:30 AM on some weekend nights. I wake up, do my routine of skin care, have a little snack in my room (I skip breakfast), and chill for a little while. Then I start studying for my classes. After studying for a little bit, I get hungry and go to the dining commons to eat lunch. Then I go back to my room and study again. If I have time and if I feel like studying with friends, I bus or drive to my friend's apartments to socialize or talk with them. Occasionally, I go to my friend's apartment to party, play some games, and drink. On Some Sundays, I also work on a night shift in the dorms where I interact with my residents and update them on things that are happening in the week. After my shifts are over (around 12:30 AM), I go back to my room and continue studying until I feel tired.

Monday: If I have energy, I will go to my 8 AM classes but sometimes I will sleep in. I have many friends in that class and the professor is engaging. After the 8 AM class, I go back to my dorms, have breakfast, and study in the dorms and relax. At 12:30 PM, I go and eat lunch at the dining commons. Then, I walk to class, where I have class 1-4 PM. I go back to the dorms and rest. I usually have a night shift for the dorms, where I do admin work of making posters, and creating program events for my residents.

Tuesday and Thursdays: I only have one class this day at 9-10:30 AM. Then I go to my internship from 1-5 PM. On both of the days, I have also have a night admin shift in the dorms. These days feel overwhelming sometimes because I have to have good time management and energy in doing both jobs.

Wednesdays: I feel the most overwhelmed on this day. I have class 8-4 PM. I also have lab that day, which makes me feel stressed out because the lab work is individual work and not with partners. After class, I have a Community Advisor shift from 6-12:30 AM. I do my program events on Wednesday for my residents, where my residents get a chance to do interactive and fun events with me. A lot of my residents come, which I am glad that they appreciate my efforts in building a community. However, Wednesdays are really tiring as I do not have time for myself. Sometimes, I get emotional of how little time I have to relax, time for myself, or studying time. My whole day is gone just from school and work.

Fridays: I have class 8 AM and 1 PM. However, I don't go to those classes (unless I have to) for my internship. I work 8-5 PM those days. Sometimes after my internship, I go to my friend's house to hang out or party. I also sometimes am shifted on Friday evenings so I stay and relax. Overall, other than working on Fridays, I feel that it is my least stressful day.

name: Tony Li
GenItems_narr:
I'm a night owl of the night owls. My brain gets very active at nights, typically starting at 8 pm. Another reason resulting in me staying up late is my college schedule. My body is much used to my biological clock, so I need a very strict schedule that is same or very similar every day. In college, my daily schedule and quarterly schedule frequently change, making it difficult for me to stick with a consistent schedule. Back to the topic, since I stay up late usually (recently I've been sleeping around 3 or 4 am), I also get up late, often after noon, which does not concern me at all. I've lived enough years to figure out that everything about me does not work well in the morning. I almost always feel drowsy and my body getting "soft" as well as my brain getting heavy, even if I have slept for enough hours within a healthy and consistent schedule. In the afternoon, my body is active and I often feel energetic, so I prefer going outdoors in the afternoon, to go to classes, to play sports, to resolve errands (like going to the bank, shopping for groceries, etc.), to hang out with friends, and so on. At night, I do a lot of brain work, including homework assignments, reading things (such as emails, mails, internet messages), and many more. I can do anything above at anytime, but I just prefer to do certain things at certain times as it appears to me that my brain or body adapts to it better. My emotional state is very stable, hardly with ups and downs. I barely have what I categorize as "extremely negative feelings," such as anger, fear, etc. Even if I feel one of these at a certain time, it goes away quickly, usually about 5 or 10 minutes later. I call these extremely negative feelings because I think these feelings are very harmful for me, with no benefits to come. Sadness is also negative, but sometimes it produces insight or inspiration, at least for me; therefore, I don't consider sadness to be extremely negative. I sometimes feel emotional at nights, as my brain gets active. I have intense feeling of empathy and compassion, and I like to listen to music while singing along with it. Thus, sometimes I would feel really emotional when listening and singing those emo songs.

I will also talk about my hobbies in short. I love having fun from video games and watching videos. I don't play video games a lot, but I like to gain joy from playing as well as to train my reflex and to practice strategizing during the game play. I watch videos mostly from YouTube and Bilibili (a Chinese video platform). There are some video makers I subscribe to as I like their video content. One thing in particular about me watching videos is that I don't like paying to watch things. Paying for a membership makes me feel that I should watch as much as possible to "make my money count," which clearly will stop me from enjoying watching videos. As I mentioned in the first paragraph, I like playing sports and hanging out with friends too. Playing sports is a good way to exercise while having fun at the same time. I mostly play badminton with my friends, and that's been really fun and motivating for me. Hanging out with friends is my major way of going outdoors. I'm not a fan of traveling, so I usually do not care about where we go; I just prefer to have some outdoor times with friends since apparently, staying indoors for too long is not healthy for us.
CT_2: quiet at start but talkative when feeling more familiar

name: Annelise Gregory
GenItems_narr:
Most days, I am energetic and motivated to attend classes and study, however, I am always tired and sluggish on Tuesday's when I have a back to back 8 and 9am class. I love being around friends and family, however, I prefer to do work and study on my own in quiet places. I would describe myself as talkative and friendly as long as I am comfortable with the people around me and the vibe is positive. 
    I have very high expectations of myself and have a strong desire to succeed. Whether, this is meeting my physical, mental, or academic goals, I always strive to get what I want. As of recent, I've been prioritizing my mental health and well-being and learning to respect and be kinder to myself. Due to this and my overall desire to succeed, I've been putting my needs first and caring about myself and being at peace a lot more.
    I work out a lot as a means of stress relief and to keep up my physical health. I love being outdoors and in nature to clear my head and reflect on  my thoughts.

name: Paul George
GenItems_narr:
I'm usually depressed because I feel like I've not achieved much in life as my peers but my mood changes whenever I take some CBD pills.I express myself better and sleep better whenever I'm on the pills.
I some days I miss my duties and classes due to anxiety and I feel like everything should stop because I've not achieved my  daily goals. I've been fired from a fast food joint that I was working before due to not showing up in work when my anxiety escalate.
My happy days are when I hang out with my family Barbecuing,baking and having some beers with them. I feel like my family triggers my first gen identity the most.
I really don't like having classes after lunch on most days because alot is always on my mind at that time and I'm mostly tired.

name: Ariana Noble
GenItems_narr:
I would describe myself as a very strong, independent person. I attend all of my classes and get good grades. I strive to do so well in school to make my family proud of me ands to prove to myself that I am worthy. My weekly schedule wasn't supposed to be too stressful but I am a person who needs to be busy to feel fulfilled. 
Mondays and Wednesdays are virtually the same. I start out with my 9am class with one of my close friends so I'm always excited to see her and go to class. I think what makes that class so exciting is the discussions I have with my classmates because I love meeting new people and getting to know them. After I usually wait in the library or SCC and do homework until 12 and we go to the gym together. I enjoy going to the gym because it helps me with my insecurities and makes me feel productive which makes me feel worthy. After the gym I go home and make myself a salad (I meal prep over the weekend so I just put the ingredients together), then I take a shower and get ready to go to my last class of the day with my roommate. The class isn't necessarily interesting but I like sitting in lecture and feeling like I'm learning something. After class we take the bus home together and I take a nap. Every day around 3-5pm I get a wave of exhaustion and sleep for 30 minutes to an hour. I then proceed to do homework and talk with my roommates which is the highlight of my day because it feels safe, comfortable, and relaxing to catch up about our day. I try to go to sleep early but I usually don't fall asleep until 1am because my mind is racing at night. I think this is because its dark and quiet so I feel free to think about imaginary scenarios in my head. 

On Tuesdays my class doesn't start until 10:30am so I wake up around 8am to make myself my daily breakfast wrap and get ready to take the bus. If I don't make my daily breakfast wrap I feel like I've messed up my whole day; one thing I've realized about myself is that I need to have a daily structured routine to feel sane and accomplished. On the bus I always take that time to catch up on social media or play games in my iphone which calms me down and gets me ready for campus. Another one of my friends is in this class with me but I wish she wasn't since she talks the entire lecture and I can't focus on taking notes (which makes me feel unaccomplished and behind in school). After the class ends I go grab a Peet's coffee and hang out with another one of my friends at the SCC. I love our weekly meetings because we catch up on our lives and complain about our boyfriends while drinking coffee and laughing. It feels like a stress-relief for the day. After that I go home since I don't have any more classes and clean the apartment because cleaning is how I relax myself and feel accomplished. 

I dread Thursdays. I'm on campus from 9:50am to 6pm with barely any breaks and I'm so tired by the end of the day because I didn't get my mid-day nap. I hate my CMN discussion because I'm so confused in the class and always fail the lab quizzes. The class makes me feel stupid and discourages me to try harder to improve. One thing I've struggled with throughout my life is when I'm not automatically good at something I lose motivation and get so mad at myself for not knowing how to do something. After the day is over I go home and take a nap and try to do some more homework. 

Fridays are easier because I only have 1 class but its a 2 hour math lecture and I hate math (probably because I'm not good at it). After that I go home and I've usually made plans with one of my friends to go out and get food or just to hang out. Sometimes my friends overwhelm me so I just stay in my room and listen to music and go on my phone for a bit. I'll hang out with my boyfriend and go to a party with him at night. I love going to parties because it's a way to get away from school and to let loose and dance and laugh with my friends. I wouldn't trade that time together for anything.

name: Isabella Cruz
GenItems_narr:
Each day is typically different. I live in student on campus housing and frequently socialize with those around me, resulting in feeling quite tired at the end of the day. I would definitely say I'm a little bit more on the emotional side and all of my personalities can show that. I have a long distance boyfriend, and would say my softest personality comes out with him. Everyday, I spend a lot of time texting and talking to him.

I spend a great amount of time with technology as my classes are recorded and mostly asynchronous. Everyday I typically have an assignment due every night. With 24 units, school is primarily on my mind and causes stress. I would say my biggest challenge right now is school and financial stresses. While I do have a job, hours have been cut and although it's given me more opportunities to study- money has been harder.
GenItems_Unique_item_2: quite tired at the end of the day

name: Chinmaya Lele
GenItems_narr:
I'm a very cold person and usually diplomatic to people. I think that strategy works well for me and I like to stick to it. Since I've roommates, I believe in texting things instead of verbally speaking. The reason I do this because its important to document conversations in a future scenario where there might be inter roommate conflict. The written texts will help a lot in arguing. I do a lot of roommates like picking up their packages and letters because there's risk of those packages get stolen. I describe myself as an 'over responsible and overly mature' roommate' .

Most of the work is done by me like cleaning common kitchen spaces, bathroom, toilet bowel. I'm the elder roommate and the other 2 are very immature which often leads me to get frustrated, sometimes going to the point of over tiring myself because I take initiative in a lot of things like cleaning but others don't show. That's why I hate them for their incompetency, their behavior is like a typical bachelor who doesn't give a shit about dirt and cleanliness in the house. Sometimes, I wish if only my financial situation was better, I'd live alone than handle all the tantrums. 
Like I said earlier, I'm a cold person so that's why I don't talk to my roommates because I'm always upset with them. Therefore, there is no point in talking to them.

name: Bethany Qamer
GenItems_narr:
Typically, I would describe my daily routine as a struggle to find energy to be able to get my brain to cooperate with the rest of my body. I have a lot of ideas, goals, dates, and responsibilities that I write down in my journal because I tend to be very forgetful. Most days, I don't meet most of those goals because I overwhelm myself with too many things I need to do. Going to classes on campus can be a bit of a struggle, since I have a lot of morning classes that I don't really like to wake up for. If it's recorded, I'll usually stay home. If it's mandatory, I'll always make it albeit rather late at times. When I am on campus though, I'll make the most of the time I have on campus and study somewhere where there's a lot of people. I like being in the presence of people, even if I'm not talking to them, and I'd consider myself an extrovert because of this.

I also find that I am a very creative person, and I have a lot of ideas that I would love to execute if not for my poor time management. I have a tendency to start something and then not end up finishing it because I either lose interest or get too busy. It's the same with school. It should also be mentioned that I'm not too great as school. I am a STEM major, but deep down I think I was meant more for a career in design or something else.

I prioritize my relationships, friends, and family above many things, and I find a lot of happiness in spending time with them. Sometimes, I'll put off responsibilities just to spend time with them, which is bad admittedly, but I don't do it all the time. Additionally, I also love being outside, going on walks, and reflecting on my thoughts. This could explain my love for writing, both creatively and otherwise. Throughout my day, I like to write whatever comes to mind in my Notes app or journal. I also have an affinity towards fashion, so I also like thinking of different designs I could make or would like to wear (though I don't have the skills to execute yet).

name: Samara Dixon
GenItems_narr:
My daily thoughts typically consist of my friends first, then academics. Physically, I normally put academics first but mentally I tend to be worrisome of my relationships I have with others based on the amount of time I allocate towards them. The way I had set up this quarter (schedule-wise) was to allow myself to feel more available on Fridays to give my (both long distance and in-person) friends the time I feel is needed. I believe I’m this way because of the way I value others, but more specifically friends. I believe I’m this way due to my negative familial circumstances when I was much younger creating an “outlet” out of my friends. Recently I haven’t been able to manage my time evenly amongst my current friends, leaving me more stressed than usual, but I do hope to fix that through confrontational communication. 

My daily schedule normally consists of early morning classes, lunch with a singular friend (almost everyday of the week), and then a few evening discussions three times a week. I try to incorporate alone time by going to the gym two times a week, and some unscheduled time being spent on social media but sometimes I feel that that is not enough. 

Academically, I am in the process of choosing a different major. I had enrolled into the school as a Biological Sciences major in hopes to go down the pre-med track, but found myself more frustrated than happy during my first year here at the school. Given the workload, course grade results, and time allocations required I ended up being more stressed than I’ve ever felt. Although I understand academics do require a set amount of time, I felt that I wasn’t given a “fair trade” in terms of personal time vs. academic time. Currently I am enrolled in prerequisite courses for Cognitive Science, in hopes to possible pursue that major, and give myself the respective time for myself as a person.
GenItems_Unique_item_3: Treating yourself is greater than treating others
GenItems_Unique_item_5: I believe that I have to find a career path soon
GenItems_Unique_item_6: Balancing time between all of your friends is important
GenItems_Unique_item_7: You should feel safe to state you need alone time
GenItems_Unique_item_9: Pursuing a different major was the right choice
GenItems_Unique_item_10: Feeling pressured to hangout with others should not be a reason for consistency

name: Mary West
GenItems_narr:
Money is a frequent topic of thought for me, and I worry about my financial standing and social status on a regular basis. I'm always considering how I can increase my wealth and improve my financial security.

My moods are greatly impacted by the people I interact with on a daily basis. When I'm surrounded by my close friends, I feel confident and sociable, and I enjoy being the life of the party. However, in unfamiliar social settings, I tend to be more reserved and quiet, as I prefer to observe and get a feel for the atmosphere before becoming more engaged.

When I'm feeling good, I sometimes act impulsively, which can lead to decisions that I later regret. To counterbalance these moments, I like to spend quality time with my loved ones, including friends and family. I value these interactions and find joy in the companionship and laughter that come with them. Additionally, I am passionate about making a positive difference in the world and I often lend my voice to causes that I believe will benefit society in the long run. I find a great deal of satisfaction in my weekly volunteer work, as it allows me to give back and feel like I'm making a meaningful impact.

name: Jocelynn Bucio
GenItems_narr:
I am not the most energetic type of person. I attend UC Davis and I scheduled my Mondays to be very easy with only one class in the afternoon to start the week. I also like to keep things pretty mellow (especially in the mornings) to prepare myself for the day. During breakfast, I mentally take note about what items to get for groceries and what chores or errands need to be done. I get anxious and stressed out easily about timing. I have difficulty preparing mine and my brothers meals everyday so that I have something for lunch between classes and so that we both have something ready for dinner by the time we head back home from work or school. I feel overwhelmed often because I also do most of the cleaning in mine and my brothers apartment. I have mentioned this to him but nothing has changed.
At school, I enjoy my classes but I dread having to make conversation with other students when asked. I have always been shy and nobody ever suspects, but I am roughly about 10 years older than any of the students in my classes. They are always so surprised to learn my actual age because I look younger than I am. I did not have the opportunity to go to college after high school, so I am back to get my bachelors degree. I am also a first generation student and it has always been my dream and goal to attend a university. Even though I enjoy my classes, many times I feel completely lost and don't speak up because I feel so out of place and dumb compared to how other students articulate their thoughts and questions during lectures and discussions. Most of the time, I do not see any other Mexican or Latin American student in my classes so that also adds to how I do not feel as comfortable speaking up.
I am back at school mostly for me but also for my mom. She has not had an easy life and I want to give her everything after graduating so that she does not have to work anymore. When I am in my bedroom at the end of the day, I give my mom a call to ask about her day and I always feel better after talking with her. She gives me the strength to continue trying and lifts my mood. It is very comforting to know she has always had my back and was the only one who believed me and understood when I was diagnosed with an anxiety and panic disorder (along with PTSD) when I was 20. Since that diagnosis, I feel like it is a never-ending work in progress. Exercise has helped me with this in the past and I used to workout daily sometimes even twice a day before attending UC Davis. However, I stopped working out completely the first quarter I started school. I had a very difficult time adjusting living away from home, but this quarter I now try to squeeze in at least 3 workout sessions for at least 30 minutes each every week.
I have a very supportive and optimistic boyfriend. He lives in Los Angeles and we see each other once a month for a straight week to deal with the distance. We have been together for 2 years and he will be coming up to stay with me soon in February. I always enjoy our time together the most because he is such a positive person and we get to dine at new restaurants and explore places together. I used to go out all the time and travel often before attending UC Davis. I actually met my boyfriend on a random boating tour in Cabo San Lucas, Mexico. Spending time together gives me a break from what seems my daily grind so that is when I am the happiest. We also work very well together with chores and errands when we stay at each others places so that makes me happy too. When he is away, he gives me little pep talks and encouragment when I have a hard time at school so those mean a lot to me too. Graduating from university would be so fulfilling for me so I am very glad he understands how important this is for me.
When I am alone and have free time, I like to draw or paint. It is very relaxing and that also makes me happy. It is another way I get to "escape".  Going to school is not easy but I will finally be able to start a career doing something I love and that will make it all worth it. I will be visiting my mom in Salinas this coming weekend too so I am looking forward to that as well. My nephew and niece also live with her so I always enjoy seeing how much they've grown since the last time I've seen them and spend time with them too. I think about having children of my own soon so that is another reason I want to finish school. Now as I am writing this, I think maybe I feel so overwhelmed because school is such a huge part to my life schedule. I didn't have a chance to finish before and now I need to get it done so that I can move on quickly to the next phase in my life now that I am in my 30's.

name: Simone Nelson
GenItems_narr:
Right now, I would say I’m doing very well. Last quarter, I decided to take a PELP leave for my mental health in order to receive treatment for depression. Initially, the first few weeks were hard because I felt so much shame about feeling this way and like I didn’t “deserve” to receive treatment. After about two months of therapy, health education classes, and medication, I began to feel better. I have experienced some family changes in the past month, including the separation of my parents. Had I not received depression treatment earlier, I don’t know if I could have handled this in the healthy way that I believe I am now. 

Part of my depression caused/or came from negative core beliefs about myself that impacted my relationships with others. I am a third year student, but last year was my first year on campus due to COVID. I had a hard time making close friends. I don’t have a ton of friends in Davis right now, but am really making strides this quarter to just try to be more connected with people, even if I don’t become “best friends” with them. A lot of interpersonal stress in my life came from avoidance and not asserting emotional boundaries. I am very introverted and need a lot of time to recharge, so I have to be careful about how much time I spend with others so I don’t feel drained. 

My day-to-day life right now is very focused around school and getting back into a routine. On Mondays, I have a therapy appointment in the morning. I used to feel anxious about these, but I have developed trust with my therapist and feel very light and free after my sessions. Then I go to business writing class, which I absolutely LOVE so far. I love writing and am planning to minor in it, so this is a great class for me. Then I have a break for a few hours, and usually head home to make lunch. I love cooking, and so I let myself get creative in the kitchen to fix a healthy meal with whatever ingredients I have on hand. After lunch and some rest, I get ready for my last class of the day. I head to my special studies in politics class, where I learn about foreign-aid and international development. I sometimes feel anxious in this class, because I feel like the energy in poli-sci classes can be a bit grating sometimes. Though I think this recent discovery has helped me realize what environments I’d like to work in post-grad. After taking the bus home, I make some dinner for myself. I work on some homework, complete some readings, and do whatever tasks I need to do for school. If I have free time, I’ll call my family and/or text my friends from home. I’ve been trying to stay more in touch with my friends back home to try to stay connected to people. If I am done with everything, I’ll watch a youtube video or a TV show until I get tired. I do my skincare routine, brush my teeth, and wind down for bed. Part of my nighttime routine is yoga nidra/yogic sleep, where I’ll stretch and meditate for about 20 minutes. After this, I get into bed and put on an audiobook, video essay, or lecture to fall asleep too. I do this instead of watching TV because I don’t have to stare at the screen and it feels *slightly* more sleep hygienic than watching TV. 

On Tuesday, I wake up at 7:30 to get ready for my 9am class. I get ready as fast as possible, and try to make a nutritious breakfast before I leave. This class is agricultural development, which I absolutely love and decided and want to pursue as a minor. I feel so valued and appreciated in this class — the professor is incredibly kind and values each and every one of our opinions. A lot of the work is focused on group discussion and reflective work, which is such a change from my other analytical classes. After this class, I head to my sheep lab discussion. I decided to take this class because I wanted to do something different (and lambs!). I was nervous about taking this as a social science major, but I decided to go for it anyways. After this, I head to my economics class. This is my least favorite class — economics professors are knowledgeable but can be extremely arrogant in my opinion. I love economics, so I do enjoy the content though. After this, I have about an hour before my next class. I’ll walk around campus and grab some lunch. Then I head to my agricultural development discussion section. I really enjoy and look forward to this class. I have made a few acquaintances in this class, and want to try to foster those friendships this year. After this, I have about an hour and a half where I can head home. I eat a snack and do any work I have to complete. Then I head back out for my economics discussion section. I don’t love this section, I often feel confused and like I’m behind when in this class.  Repeat monday night routine.

Wednesday: I wake up at 7, and bundle up in warm clothes for my sheep lab! I wanted to interact with the animal side of UCD, so I decided to take an animal science course about sheep. I head down to the Sheep Barn around 8am, and am feeling energized and excited. I feel a sense of calm hearing the quiet of the morning. It depends on the day, but so far we have seen the newborn lambs, which brings me lots of joy. After hardwork at the sheep barn, I head to my business writing class. I enjoy this class and am entertained by the professor. I have a few hours break, so I’ll usually head back to my apartment and make lunch. After resting for a little, I head out to my political science class. I don’t dislike this class, but it isn’t my favorite — I tend to not enjoy the people in my polisci classes as much. I head home after this, and get to work on my homework. Make dinner and repeat nightly routine. 

Thursday: I wake up at 7:30 and get ready for my IAD class. I head to the bus at 8:30 and have class from 9-10:30. I feel good after this class because I really like the professor and the people in it. Then I stop for some coffee/tea and try to find Cheeto while I walk past the physics building. Then I put in some music and go for a walk through the Arboretum to my economics class. I feel good on Thursday mornings because I finish early since I don’t have sections today! After my econ class, I try to do something fun to relieve stress. Then I rest as much as I can because I still treat Fridays as a work day, even though I don’t have any classes. Repeat night routine. 

Friday: I let myself sleep in until around 8:30 or 9 to catch up on sleep for the week, but I try to head out in the mornings to run errands. I find that it helps me to give myself a task so I don’t just lay around all day, which leads me to feeling depressed. I make sure to work on some school work, but also do something good for the soul. I’ll take a walk, go to a used bookstore, go swimming, or go to a UCD teaching kitchen class! I am making sure to prioritise wellness from now on, and that means doing things that feed my soul. I’m going to start volunteering for things that are important to me, like community food security, helping community cat colonies, and learning about local agricultural industries. I feel that my recent depressive episode actually led to a huge life shift, and even though I wouldn’t wish that on myself if I could go back, I feel like I learned a lot through that experience.

name: Haley Major
GenItems_narr: I like to go to the gym at least 4 times a week or I start to get anxious. I usually feel really energized right after working out but tend to get a little sleepy around 2 hours post-gym. I used to be a really disciplined student but lately it's been harder for me to be proactive with deadlines. I still turn in all of my assignments on time, but not as early as I'd like. I usually go to all of my classes because I like in-person school the most. I love seeing people I know on campus but since I'm a transfer student that can be challenging. I love all of my roommates and enjoy hanging out with them. I wish we could be closer, though, because some of them were better friends with each other than me when we all first moved in. We like spending time together as a household and we love the farmers market, watching movies, baking, and going out together. My personal relationships are a huge part of my life and I enjoy getting to spend time with my boyfriend, too. I'm not as close with my family and I don't spend much time talking to them on the phone. Sometimes I wish I had more time to socialize but I'm often busy with school and my research lab. I work as a tester in the BASC lab. I'm very perfectionistic and detailed driven. People would describe me as assertive, but empathetic. I also think I'm really driven to do the things I want and can lack patience when things don't go my way. I'm also really organized. I think I have an ok sense of humor. I love going out to parties and I like to go to bars/ public settings.

name: Ethan Percival
GenItems_narr:
I wake up energized (usually around 8 am), but am usually tired by 10 am. I think going from moving around a lot in the morning, with my entire morning routine, to going to the dining commons, and then just sitting down for an hour and a half in class makes me tired. I’ve realized I’m only yawning at one specific time, in one specific class. I have that class twice a week, and it happens twice a week, and only in that class.
I feel pretty distanced from my friends, and am slowly trying to find other connections on campus. I feel pretty lonely most of the time, but I have a lot of coursework to do that takes up most of my day anyways.
My parents are very successful, so I feel like I have a lot of pressure on myself, and from them as well. I’m struggling to find friends that I can rely on. A lot of my friends want me to to rely on them, but I’ve tried multiple times, and they haven’t been very supportive, or even worse-unsupportive with any issues I’m facing in my life. 
I want to join clubs and do more activities on campus, but with such a complicated schedule and workload, it makes doing much of anything difficult.

name: Reignelle Jaeshree Ramos
GenItems_narr:
Nowadays, I feel as though my motivation fluctuates quite a bit. When I'm alone with my thoughts, I seem to have no will to do my assignments or any productive thing I can do. I'm a bit of a perfectionist and someone who gets easily bored. So not only does starting a goal seem undesirable in the sense that I would never be able to complete it to the standards that I want them to, I just lack the attention span needed to begin it in the first place.
I also get stressed out about returning to my apartment as my roommates are very messy and tend to leave the common areas like the living room and kitchen in disarray. Usually, I'm left to clean up these areas, leaving me drained by the end of it all. Although, I do derive satisfaction from the order I had restored.

name: Siddhartha Bali
GenItems_narr:
During the weekdays, I have classes every day in the mornings. I love this because my brain is extremely active in the mornings! I wake up at 6 am on weekdays and immediately jump into the shower. This helps me not waste any time on my phone. 
I shower and eat breakfast. From that, I walk to class.
Until this point, I am usually thinking about the day and hyping myself to study well. If I end up on my phone in bed, that ruins my mood cause my eyes hurt and I start to feel lethargic. 

My tiredness does hit me after lunch. That's usually when I go back to my room and study a little. Usually revising stuff I learned in the morning. 
I am excited about attending all my classes except my ENG100 class cause the professor is not good and the lab class is extremely tedious and tough. Being forced to work on circuits for three hours straight is not really learning inducive and ends up becoming something we just want to finish and leave.
I head to the gym at 3 pm and got good music with pumps me up.
I like to erg (rowing machine) since I used to row for UCDavis and I absolutely love doing it. After that its some light weights and I am done.

The rest of the evening is my job work and homework. I work as a RA in the dorms and love the job.!

name: Caitlyn Ho
GenItems_narr: I tend to wake up early (for my standards) at around 9 am but I usually don't get out of bed until 11. I'm not sure why but it's really hard for me to get out of bed. For me, the day starts at around 12pm, which is lunch time. If I eat too much I'll feel tired after lunch but if not I'll be fine for the day. I usually don't study well in the afternoon. My brain tends to activate after dinner time and I study until 1 or 2 am. I would consider myself an emotional person but I find that I have the ability to think logically. I am able to think logically but my emotions tend to get in the way. I also tend to repeat scenarios in my head. I am a really big planner, and when things don't go according to plan I find myself triggered and annoyed. I lack patience, but around certain people I can control my emotions. As for the social aspect of my life, when I meet new people I can be awkward but usually there is a certain point in the friendship where I can let loose and be myself. Sometimes I feel out of place and stupid and other times I feel like I belong and I'm really smart. I'm not sure if I could characterize myself as smart or not. Even after looking at my grades, I still wouldn't have an answer if someone asked me if I was smart or not. I can put up an act in front of other people. For example, I'm currently going through a breakup of a 2 year relationship but even so, I hide my sadness in front of peers because I don't want to burden them. The friends around me tell me that I don't seem sad and that this breakup seems as if it doesn't affect me, but in reality I am deeply affected deep down, I just try myself to put up an act.

name: Michelle Chew
GenItems_narr:
My normal day-to-day is pretty smooth in terms of thoughts, energy, and emotions. I wake up to one alarm at 8:20 each morning not particularly energized, but definitely not groggy and sluggish like a cartoon would portray a non-morning person. I stay in bed on my phone for a few minutes, eat breakfast, wash up, and go. The 10-minute bike ride to school is usually pleasant (especially if I play music on the way), though I admit rainy and extremely cold days worsen my mood. 
   I don't actively keep track of my thoughts. I think they mostly have to do with the tasks I'm focused on and the things I have to complete and convincing myself not to spend $5 on a matcha latte. I think nighttime is more loose in thought for me. I think about random things and wonder about how friends are doing. Oftentimes thoughts surrounding self-reflection come when I talk with friends, especially when we talk about deeper subjects. When I don't have anything to do, such as when I'm waiting in line for something or taking a mental break, my thoughts are very quiet- I don't think I think about anything at all usually. I'm also a pretty emotionally stable person. It's hard to get me angry about something, and I'm typically either calm, happy, or slightly stressed because of schoolwork at any point of the day. 

   Tuesdays and Thursdays I have class non-stop from 9am until 3 or 4pm, and I often go from a very awake, aware state, to drifting off (and occasionally napping in my middle class), to awake and slightly distracted during class time. 
   Mondays and Wednesdays I only have one class at 1pm, so I stay in bed for a couple hours and cook myself a (usually) healthy lunch before class, where I stay attentive and thoughtful throughout. During all of my classes, I like to have my planner open so I can update assignments immediately and remind myself of upcoming deadlines so I know how I can schedule my afternoons. 
Fridays I have no class, so I count it as part of the weekend. I often try and catch up on schoolwork, host a dinner with friends, run errands, and relax. I also recently got a job as a UC Davis tour guide, so I schedule training sessions on Fridays and get paid to study the script if I go into the Welcome Center on Saturday mornings. I try to make the most of it. 

   I'm very comfortable around peers and professors, with no social anxiety or awkwardness, though in my LDA classes many of my peers have their own social circles that I sometimes feel I should have within my department. Overall, I feel pretty belonged at Davis and at my hometown. I find friends of similar cultures and mindsets, and while I learn from and experience differences with some peers at school, it's never felt hostile or uncomfortable to me. 

   As an overview of myself, I'd like to start by saying I am a Christian. It's been pretty foundational to the way I've been raised and the way I view things and go about life. I identify as a cis female, Asian-American and Chinese, and as a beloved child of God. I am not anxious nor depressed, and I like to think I take pretty good care of myself mentally and physically. If I'm feeling extremely tired, I would rather take a late assignment or email a professor about an extension rather than pull an all-nighter. I try to put my well-being above my studies, my studies above my social life, and my social life above staying at home and wasting my life away watching cat videos on Instagram. 
   My social life is pretty nice, if I do say so myself. My main friend group is from a Christian club on campus, that meets Tuesdays and Thursdays formally, and often hangs out randomly throughout the week as well. I try to invite a few of them out to dinner at least once a week. I also have a couple friends outside of my club, whom I coordinate a weekly study session with at the beginning of each quarter or randomly get together with every once in a while. When I'm with my friends, you could usually spot me smiling. I love being with them, and they always make me laugh. I enjoy hearing their life stories and joking around with them. Sometimes going to small or large group for club meetings can feel stressful because I need to coordinate my schedule around it and do my homework ahead of time, but at the same time I'm usually excited to go and it's always worth it in the end. I enjoy spontaneous, unplanned hangouts very much, and I'll find myself spending an hour or two with a friend randomly at least once or twice a week. 
   Some of my goals in life are to simply do good works, be the best person I can be, and follow Jesus as best I can. The biggest challenges I face in the day-to-day are staying on top of schoolwork and balancing my work-life well. I often wish I had more time to be with friends, or that I spent more time seeking after God, or that I could bring myself to learn fun things in my free time or exercise, but oftentimes my tiredness, laziness, and schoolwork prevent me from doing those things.

name: Joyce Pau
GenItems_narr:
I'm a first-year Design major, with plans to also major in Communications and minor in Tech Management. I'm typically a happy person. I like to believe that there's good in everything/everyone. Raised by two immigrant parents, I grew up with strong Asian roots, so relationships is very important to me. I find myself the happiest when I'm with family or friend, especially if there's conversation over food (like when I'm eating with someone). 

My mood is usually affected if I don't get enough rest or I get too deep into thoughts that makes me upset. The past few years, I've noticed that school and trying to be a people pleaser causes me to be stressed and sometimes sad. I also struggle a bit with time management, so sometimes the reasons I stress is stemed from my previous actions. I recently got back into Christianity, so I tend to find myself in a bit of internal conflict and but too much pressure on myself to feel need to fit into the perfect mold. But, depsite the challenges I face internally or externally, I push myself to overcome them and reassure myself that everything will be okay.

name: Aya-Mei Duncan
GenItems_narr:
On Monday's, Wednesdays, and Fridays I have an 8 am, 9 am, and 10 am class. Because of this, I often get very fatigued later in the day, no matter what the rest of these days look like. I have breakfast in the morning, usually with my roomate. Every Friday I work after my classes, and on Wednesday I have a lab so tuesdays are often spent prepping and doing the pre lab after my classes and choir practice, which I have on Tuesdays and Thursdays. I’ve felt generally quite fatigued thus far in winter quarter, but I am attempting to keep my energy by writing down my tasks in a planner.

Although I love my friends, I seek some alone time throughout the day, whether that be a meal for myself or finding a quiet place to sit for a while. I eat from the dining hall but end up favoring food I can cook in my dorm, which doesn’t make me feel nearly as sick. I try to read, as I used to read a lot but I fell out of it. I’ve been reading a chapter of a book every night which is really nice

name: Shreya Chigurupati
GenItems_narr:
I tend to go through most of my day on auto-pilot, especially when I’m busy, so I don’t spend a lot of time thinking about my emotions throughout the day. I have noticed though that I feel much more relaxed when I’m on top of schoolwork and other commitments and don’t have too many things to do. I know I usually feel energetic in the mornings if I’ve had enough sleep, and I’m usually in a good mood during my morning classes. I think I enjoy my morning classes this quarter because they’re very participation based, and I like sharing my ideas with my peers and hearing their thoughts. However, after lunch I feel pretty drained, because I’m reminded of the work I need to do. I also have 2-3 hours of free time after lunch, which I usually don’t spend productively even if I try to, and this tends to stress me out. Most days of the week I have evening classes, and I find it incredibly difficult to stay focused because of these emotions, which makes me feel even worse. By the time I get home I’m exhausted, but my mood does tend to improve if I manage to finish everything I need to do in less than 4 hours. 

More generally I would say the feelings that I feel often are loneliness and a fear of the future. While I think I have a good amount of friends and I tend to talk to them frequently, I often feel like I’m putting on an act and not being myself around them, and if I were to be myself, they wouldn’t want to be around me. I don’t know if I’m actually doing this or not, and there are no concrete things I do to act like someone else, but I just feel like I’m performing as someone all the time and it makes me feel lonely. I try not to think about these things too much though.

name: Nicholas Daer
GenItems_narr:
I like to follow a general schedule day-to-day. This usually means waking up 60-90 minutes before class. This means I usually wake up between 11:30-12:30. Before class, I like to eat something I make at home, something from campus, or something from Panera. I try to go to Panera before class, because I have their membership that allows one free drink cup per day. MWF I have class until 4, TR until 5. I find my classes' material enjoyable, but find I do tend to get a bit tired at some point in class. After my last class, I like to do homework until 5:30-6, with the time I work really depending on when my last class is over. I go to the gym to run on the indoor track after I do some work, currently at around 25 minutes. After the gym, I will continue to work on work that is due soon. When I have decided I have done a sufficient amount of work, I either drive or bike over to my friend's place and hang out till around 1:30am. Whether I bike or drive is decided by what I have to bring (will drive if I have to bring more than can fit in a backpack), the weather (I don't like biking in rain and wind), and my energy level (some days I don't have the energy to bike 10-15 minutes). When I go home, I shower, brush my teeth, and go to bed, usually around 3:30am.

I like to eat my dinner at my friends place; I don't have to use the utilities at my house if I need to cook, and I find I enjoy eating more in social environments. Even when I don't have anything planned with my friends, I still go to their place just for the fact I enjoy their company. It is out of the ordinary if I do not go to their place at some point in a day.

I watch and listen to a lot of youtube and music; to an amount I feel is excessive. I find I typically don't go to bed when I maybe should because I watch youtube after I shower. Sometimes I feel like I aimlessly browse youtube or spotify so I can watch or listen to something interesting, even when I don't know what that is.

Sometimes, I notice (whether from not sleeping enough, being hungry, or not having my coffee) that I feel grumpy. However, I still try to be pleasant around those I have to interact with.

I don't talk to people I don't know or don't need to interact with. In a normal day, the only people I will talk to are my professors, my friends, or a cashier if a store doesn't have self checkout. I am not especially keen to collaborate with my classmates when tasked to.

I tend to find it annoying when people on bikes don't follow the rules of the road. As someone who uses their bike for most of their transportation needs, I find it's important to follow the same rules as a car would. As a result, it annoys me when I see bicyclist run stop signs (especially downtown), bike without lights at night, and do not yield to passing rules (cruise on the right side; pass on the right; give space on the right to pedestrians). It is also annoying to me when pedestrian walk in the middle, or to the left, in a shared bike lane.

Weekends are my personal time. I wake up whenever I wakeup (anywhere between 12:30-2:30pm), and get up to start the day once I feel it is time to get out of bed (anywhere from 10 minutes to two hours after waking up). Usually, I will take some time after I wake up to get dressed. I typically go to Panera for my daily coffee, and to take care of work if I have some. I may continue working when I get home from Panera (around 3:30-5:30pm), or I may decide to do something else (nothing specifically). No matter what I do, I will still go to my friend's place over the weekend as well.

name: Harmanpreet Kaur
GenItems_narr:
My emotions stay constant throughout the week for the past month now. I'm happy with im around my sister, friends, or family. But the only thing that affects my mood in a negative way is my relationship with my boyfriend because things aren't too great.

School is a big part of my life. I'm a pre-med student and getting into medical school is really important to me. I'm always thinking of how I can make my application better. What more I can do, what more I can add. What classes to take what quarter so I can graduate on time with at least one minor? I do hate how discussions are mostly late in the day with a huge gap because I commute. 

I do feel like I don't have an identity anymore. Like who I used to be, I'm not her. And I haven't been taking care of myself that much. I'm not consistent. I hate that about me right now. I'm trying to gain back my identity and I know I can't be the same person because I've grown from certain situations but at least gain a new identity that I love. I'm trying to eat healthy, go to the gym everyday, do my skincare every night, do what makes me happy, etc. 

It's challenging to make new friends these days for. It's hard for me to get out my comfort zone. And when I do, it doesn't just work out for me. But I know I have to be consistent to make bonds.

name: Melissa Zenteno
GenItems_narr:
I am a women in college. I have zero romantic partners. I have a fat crush on an athlete on campus and literally talk about him all the time, my favorite hobby. 

I listen to music all the time. I go to class, everyday. I try to cook the least amount possible so when I do I cook portions for a couple of days. 

I do homework all day and go to tutoring for physics. I am really struggling with physics so I have to ask there. I cook oatmeal almost everyday for breakfast. I also take the bus everyday to and from campus. 

I charge my electronics everyday and I try to do my makeup almost everyday.

name: Hannah Nguyen
GenItems_narr:
I am always stressed, and I am constantly tired. I tend to get mad at little things easily and feel like every day is a chore. I don't often feel refreshed when I wake up or feel excited/ motivated to attend classes and start my day. This happen as a result of my lack of sleep, yet I couldn't find myself sleeping earlier. I constantly find myself wanting to go out more but couldn't afford to do so because of my busy schedule, especially when I'm trying to maintain 17 units each quarter. Even though Monday, Wednesday, and Friday are my busiest days, I find myself often more unproductive and tired on Tuesday and Thursday, which I only have 1-2 classes. Ever since I attend college, I always feel behind and that my peers are doing more than me even though they have less time to put into those activities.

My everyday thoughts and feelings don't always exactly define who I am as a person either. Like other college students, I want to go out, I want to party, and to meet other people. However, there is always that nagging feeling and that dread in my stomach of untouched homework and hours of studies I have to make up in exchange for my social life. Locking myself in my room started to become a trend every time midterms and finals started to approach around the corner. I would skip meals and skip classes just to catch up on all the materials that piled up over a course of time that exist in my subconscious mind. Despite this, I feel an exhilaration while working under pressure, while catching up on weeks of lecture 2 days prior to the midterm, or even pulling all-nighters leading up to the exams.  Similarly, when I am out, the adrenaline of a carefree life excites me, and I'm allowed to really let go after an hour of being out or so. All in all, I am quite dissatisfied with the life I lead, and I know ways to improve it, yet I often find myself leaning towards last minute cramming, just to be so stressed to the point my stomach cramps and Tylenol became a basic necessity.

name: Bailey Tibbetts
GenItems_narr:
I usually am very thoughtful about my actions and things things I do everyday. I enjoy coming across to other people like I'm carefree but I like having a level of organization. It makes other people feel calm and organized when they are around someone that acts like they don't care about anything. I think it's important to take care of yourself but to do so and actually do interesting things is very difficult. I try to be really hopeful about the world, but things can be pretty bad sometimes. I think I notice a lot of patterns that people have, but I don't think there is anything useful that comes from that information. I used to think that you should just care about people and love them because there was something that you could gain from it, but now I just enjoy being around people for the fact that they are people. 

I think my relationship with sports is really interesting because I really enjoy playing water polo. It gives me a lot of confidence and makes me really happy even when I'm feeling sad. I think I care about people a lot, but sometimes I think I need to get better at setting boundaries with both others and with myself. I think I can overwork myself really easily but I think it's good that I know that because I at least have identified a possible issue.
GenItems_Unique_item_2: acts like they don't care about anything

name: Lizbet Sandoval
GenItems_narr: I am 19 years old and a sophmore student in UC Davis majoring in animal science. I love anything outdoors but also love the confort of home and watching disney movies. I am shy but when I am confortable I am very giggly and funny. I only know 3 people on campus and those are my roommates. I dont put in time to make friends because I like my personal bubble but at the same time i love having cuality time with loved ones. I dont like to share my life with no one except one special person currently in my life. I am outgoing but at the same time I dont like to be much out there and I always tru to help people out and be kind because I know the world is already hard enough. My goal is to be a vet and help as many animals as I can. I am a very simple person and there is not a lot too me
GenItems_Unique_item_13: Dont trust a lot of people
GenItems_Unique_item_15: Like being in the conforts of home

name: Anna-Sophia DeBakcsy
GenItems_narr:
I do... a lot of stuff. Pretty much every extracurricular activity I do is something music related- I'm a cellist in a trio, and a trombone in marching and campus band. While I'm practicing or performing I tend to be the happiest I think, I'm able to be totally lost in music and that can feel pretty amazing to share with other like minded musicians. To an extent, I feel the same when I'm practicing martial arts, but I don't do that quite as much since I'm far away from my dojo. So generally, I'd say my peak moments in any given week are when I perform or rehearse with my trio or bands (some combination of those things happen every day except Sunday)

Recently I've been under a lot of stress from midterms and my auditions for DCI (drum corps international, it's like... professional marching band) so I haven't really been able to relax at all, I always need to be practicing or staying on top of course work. A typical day includes maybe 2-3 hours of lecture or discussion, 1-4 hours of rehearsal, and the rest is practice or studying. Fortunately the stress hasn't gotten to my sleep I think, I've always been an Insanely deep sleeper, literally nothing on the planet can keep me from dozing off within a few minutes. Honestly, the stress from auditions and midterms isn't all too bad. There's a lot I need to be doing all of the time but I tend to prefer being busy to having long periods of time where there's nothing I really need to be doing. I like feeling productive. For that reason, I honestly really dislike transition periods between classes where you can't Really do anything- or when large chunks of time are spent transporting instruments or dropping things off at the dorm. That drives me... nuts. I also tend to be pretty unhappy while eating- I've had a really complicated relationship with food, and I honestly would just prefer if I could have a tasteless slurry that gave me all the nutrients and macromolecules I needed to live.

I think overall I've been pretty happy this quarter- last quarter was a completely different story and I genuinely thought that I would die but so far, this has been totally manageable! and I'm not taking chemistry, so that definitely improves one's mood....

name: Shamika Gavaskar
GenItems_narr: Other people typically describe me as energetic and extroverted. I try to keep this attitude on a daily basis, but sometimes I like to enjoy my alone time and relax in the comfort of my own company. Yet, I crave meeting new people and expanding on my knowledge through in person experience. In my opinion, talking is a gateway, and I make sure to communicate my thoughts and feelings with the people I love most to the best of my abilities. Even though most people would classify me as extroverted, I would say that I'm very much an ambivert, who can freely carry a conversation with a stranger but also keeps to herself at times.

name: Timothy Wong
GenItems_narr: I tend to wake up tired and feel tired throughout the day. I would say I am a night owl I have no problems staying up past 12:00am. Waking up early is a hard for me so on days where I have morning classes I feel moody. I mostly go to classes and study. When I have free time it is spent on general upkeep at home. I had hobbies previously before school started but with my current course load I have stopped them. I am generally an organized person, I plan out my daily activities in my planner/google calendar.

name: Luke Stewart
GenItems_narr:
I am multi-faceted as I try to not hold my identity within one activity such as school, track, work, or my passion for media creation. I find myself stressed when I realize I may have spread myself a little too thin. Majority of the time I think I maintain a stable emotional level. I don't think I have super high "highs" and really low "lows". I am usually determined and goal-oriented in the mornings as I try to get all of my homework done before I go to track practice. When practice comes I enjoy joking around with my teammates. I find myself the type of person that matches others' energy. I have one upperclassmen teammate that is a little to harsh sometimes to my other first-year teammate and it sometimes gets on my nerves. I try to be as nice and generous to my first-year friend as I can because I know he is incredibly shy and overthinks a lot of interactions. 

I do not like Tuesdays and Thursdays because I have an 8am writing class where attendance is mandatory. There is 4 pages of writing due prior to every class and I always procrastinate leading to me staying up late and getting terrible sleep. I hate waking up for the 8am. I often nap for three hours right after class on these days. This bad habit throws off my sleep schedule, but I usually recover come the weekend. I signed up for this specific writing class because it is a strict requirement. It has nothing to do with choice. 

In the afternoon after practice, I enjoy watching NBA basketball. I find joy in watching the players I like succeed. Sometimes I can see my mood correlate with how my favorite players or teams perform. I often hang out with my floormates in the evening. I find that my mood and mental state are determined how others (my friends) perceive me sometimes. I trust my friends opinions and judgement majority of the time, so I think this is okay.
GenItems_Unique_item_1: I often hang out with my floormates in the evening
GenItems_Unique_item_2: I hate waking up for the writing class
